<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-05 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Calls for Lifting Siege on Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today called for lifting "the siege" imposed by Israel on the
Palestinian people and resuming their security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"As long as we denounce terrorism that kills innocent people,
we should say no to the siege of the Palestinian people as well,"
Mubarak told a press conference following his meeting with Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said the best way to settle the crisis is to establish
security cooperation between the Palestinians and the Israelis, to
eliminate all obstacles facing the peace process and to build
confidence between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said he discussed with the Israeli minister the
"punitive" measures imposed on the Palestinian National Authority
following the July 30 Jerusalem bombings that killed 15 people and
injured 170 others. But he declined to go into details.
</P>
<P>
"We are against terrorism, bloodshed and killing of innocent
people and also against leaving people starved and without medical
treatment," he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that there are a number of proposed ideas on resuming
negotiations and coordination is going on with the United States,
the key mediator in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt had also been mediating between the Palestinians and
Israelis for a resumption of peace talks while the twin bomb
attacks in Jerusalem shattered the hope.
</P>
<P>
Levy arrived here today to discuss with Egyptian leaders on the
peace process. The visit came a few days ahead of another regional
tour of U.S. Mideast Envoy Dennis Ross.
</P>
<P>
Levy defended Israel's crackdown on the Palestinian-controlled
areas in the wake of Jerusalem bombings and urged the Palestinians
to uproot terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"We were forced to take these measures," he told a press
conference held after a 30-minute session with his Egyptian
counterpart Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
The aim is not to "weaken the powers of the Palestinian
National Authority nor to lead to its fall," but to create "a sort
of awareness of the importance of security cooperation and of
uprooting terrorism," Levy said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Levy is apparently taking advantage
of Egypt's influence on PNA President Yasser Arafat to pressure
the PNA to launch a war against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the PNA is doing everything possible to prevent
further deterioration of the situation and urged Israel to ease
its "collective penalty" of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Levy's visit here synchronized with an emergency meeting of the
Arab League, called by Arafat to discuss Israel's "collective
punishment" of the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the twin bomb attacks, Israel imposed tight
travel restrictions on the West Bank and Gaza, halted the transfer
of tax revenues to the PNA and suspended peace talks. It has
rounded up 156 Palestinians suspected of terrorist activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
