<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Government Pledges to Help Montserrat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The British government has pledged
to help the Caribbean island of Montserrat in reversing the
exodus of local residents from the island, which has been severely
hit by a series of powerful volcanic eruptions.
</P>
<P>
Britain's International Development Secretary Clare Short told
a press conference today after meeting with chief minister of the
British colony Bertrand Osborne that Britain would help Montserrat
by carefully developing the northern part of the island unaffected
by the active Soufriere Hills volcano.
</P>
<P>
"It is my own view that people who have left might well return
when they know what our commitment is to the north," Short said.
</P>
<P>
Short ruled out the possibility of evacuating the eastern
Caribbean island, saying a massive evacuation had "never ever been
contemplated".
</P>
<P>
Osborne said scientists had advised that about 15-16 square
miles (39-41 sq km) in the northern part were safe, giving the
possibility of a planned development of the island with suitable
housing and with a view to tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward to a new Montserrat and we are pretty
confident that we will have a new Montserrat that most
Montserratians will come back to," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook also promised
to help the people of Montserrat during his talks with Osborne on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The Government will continue to place the highest priority on
sustaining, and improving, the economic and social structure of
Montserrat," Cook said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
