<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Challenges Extra-territorial Human Rights Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- China said today that no country
should impose its domestic laws on the rest of the world with
regard to human rights.
</P>
<P>
The rule of law should not be distorted into a self-claiming
authority of a big power to impose its internal law on the rest of
the world on the pretext of protecting universal human rights, a
Chinese human rights expert told a meeting of a sub-commission of
the U.N. Human Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
"Any resolution adopted in the legislative body of a single
state ... has no competence whatsoever beyond its boundary and can
in no way be accepted as a supra-national legal instrument," Fan
Guoxiang told the 49th session of the Sub-Commission on Prevention
of Discrimination and Protection of Minorities.
</P>
<P>
The current session will last until August 29. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
