<HEADLINE> S.Africa-Lesotho Meeting Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The South African and
Lesotho governments today dismissed a report that President
Nelson Mandela had invited delegations from the Lesotho
government and the country's three major opposition parties to a
meeting in Pretoria on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's spokesman Parks Mankahlana told the press: "We know
nothing about such a meeting."
</P>
<P>
Thomas Thabane, Special Adviser to Prime Minister Ntsu
Mokhehle of Lesotho, said today in Mbabane: "I think this is a
make-up story by opposition parties."
</P>
<P>
Lesotho's opposition parties also denied the report.
</P>
<P>
Basutoland Congress Party (BCP) Deputy Leader Tsheliso
Makhakhe said the reported Pretoria meeting with delegations from
South Africa, Botswana and Zimbabwe was " a fabrigation".
</P>
<P>
"We have had nothing to do with such information at all and we
have never had anything from Mr.Mandela on the reported meeting,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
An international news agency on Sunday quoted a BCP spokesman
as saying Mandela had invited delegations from the Lesotho
government, the BCP and other two oppositions to a meeting in
Pretoria August 6 to discuss Lesotho's political situation.
</P>
<P>
The other two opposition parties are the Basotho National
Party and Marematlou Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe and president ketumile
Masire of Botswana were also reported to be coming to the
meeting. Endidtem


