<HEADLINE> Samaranch Slams Nagano Organizers over Downhill Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- International Olympic Committee
(IOC) chief Juan Antonio Samaranch on Tuesday hit out at the
organisers of next year's Nagano Winter Olympics for refusing to
address a bitter row over the Alpine skiing downhill.
</P>
<P>
The International Ski Federation (FIS) want the downhill
starting point put further up the slope because the run will be
too short.
</P>
<P>
But Nagano chiefs have refused, saying it would break
environmental laws because it would take the start into a national
park.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch said: "Thousands of skiers use this zone during the
weekend. The zone is not protected...It is not easy to
understand, even for myself...The FIS is still insisting for
change."  
</P>
</TEXT>
