<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Companies to Put Video Network on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The MCI Communications
Corporation, the second largest player in the telecommunication
industry in the U.S., is expected to offer a service that will
permit computer users simultaneously to receive video broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
By using the technology of a small new company in Seattle
called Progressive Networks, MCI wishes to let computer users to
watch both live and on-demand broadcasts, according to a report by
the New York Times today.
</P>
<P>
Although the alliance with Progressive Networks is another step
in the convergence of television and the Internet, experts said
there are sill considerable barriers in producing
television-quality programs by way of the Internet. The images are
small and motion is often jerky or sometimes nonexistent because
of network congestion.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem, MCI and Progressive Networks planned to
distribute copies of digital video programs to many points in
MCI's Internet backbone. The so-called multicast capability of the
Realnetwork system will permit as many as 50,000 users to view it
simultaneously and as many as 10 million to 15 million people
daily to tune in to digital programs on their PC's, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The two companies said that the project will be profitable
even though they will reach far smaller audiences than are now
reached by broadcast television.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
