<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt, Oil Firms Clash over Price Fixing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government and the
oil industry are in dispute over what the authorities called unfair
pricing of petroleum products by oil companies, the Daily Nation
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government appears impatient with the way the eight local
oil companies are pricing their products and has gone to the
extent of threatening to re-introduce price controls if the
industry fails to regulate itself.
</P>
<P>
However, the oil companies, argue that pricing policies are
dictated by market forces and are, therefore, unlikely to change
simply for the sake of pleasing the authorities.
</P>
<P>
The standoff heightened last week when the government hinted
at a high level meeting with the oil industry players that it
might be forced to put in place some controls over retail prices
of petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Kenyan Minister for Energy Kirugi M'Mukindia accused
the oil firms of being too quick in raising retail prices of
their products "at the slightest excuse" while dragging their
feet to reduce prices when international crude oil prices
dropped.
</P>
<P>
Only last month, some oil companies delayed reducing pump
prices by up to two weeks following the lowering of international
crude oil prices, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said that the government would find it hard
to re-introduce price controls without upsetting other key
sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
They said that re-introduction of controls would not be viewed
well in terms of the financial reforms that had been going on
over the last few years, and could be seen as a "complete
turnaround" in government policies.
</P>
<P>
They also charged the government of sometimes failing to take
into account the factors that are critical in the pricing of oil.
</P>
<P>
Although the prices of crude oil in the world market has
stabilized at slightly over 18 Dollars per barrel, a slight
depreciation of the Shilling would have a very severe effect on
retail prices, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
With the suspension of aid by the International Monetary Fund
announced last week, the shilling is expected to continue
depreciating further pushing procurement costs higher.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation has already started taking its toll. Last
week all oil companies except Mobil increaseed their prices by
between 40 cents and 60 cents to reflect the change in the
Shilling's exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
The shilling suffered further on Friday, dropping to 60
Shillings the dollar range. Before riots rocked the eastern
African country on July 7 with 13 killed, the shilling had
stablized at 55 shilling against one dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britons Are Much More Found of Chocolate than Others </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain is a nation of
chocoholics, consuming much more chocolate per head than any other
European country.
</P>
<P>
The average consumer in the UK spends 91.11 US dollars a year
on chocolate, eating almost 14kg annually, according to a survey
by Datamonitor, the management consultants.
</P>
<P>
Altogether, Britons spend 5.3 billion US dollars a year on
chocolate, a quarter more than Europe's second largest market,
Germany (4.3 billion US dollars), and substantially more than the
number three market, France (2.1 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ireland comes a close second, with average consumers spending
90.39 on 13.72kg a year.
</P>
<P>
Belgium and Switzerland, renowned for their chocolate-making
skills, rank numbers four and eight in the chocoholics league
table of per capita spending.
</P>
<P>
The chocolate market in Europe was now worth more than 30
billion US dollars, and no one was contributing more to this
figure than the British, Datamonitor said.
</P>
<P>
The total chocolate market in western Europe is 18.5 billion US
dollars, up from 16.8 billion US dollars in 1992.
</P>
<P>
According to Roccoco, one of Britain's retailer of hand-made
chocolates, the British love affair with chocolate is becoming
ever more adventurous.
</P>
<P>
Consumers are moving away from traditional milk chocolate to
bitter dark bars, and flavors such as chilli and Earl Grey are
selling well, Roccoco said.
</P>
<P>
Chocolate has been credited with a number of unique qualities
since it was introduced to Europeans by Spanish explorer Hernan
Cortes in early 16th century.
</P>
<P>
Most recently doctors claimed that chocolate could help in the
prevention of heart attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
