<HEADLINE> Sacramento Wins Women's 1,500m World Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Carla Sacramento of Portugal won the
women's 1,500 meters gold medal with a time of four minutes 4.24
seconds here today at the 6th World Athletics Championships.
</P>
<P>
The silver and bronze were won by Regina Jacobs of the United
States in 4:04.63 and Anita Weyermann of Switzerland in 4:04.70.
</P>
<P>
The race saw the field roll forward like a tight knot with Malin
Eweriof of Sweden leading the pace. Jacobs, the 1997 world leader and
U.S. champion, and Sacramento, world bronze medallist in 1995, stayed
close behind the leader.
</P>
<P>
Jacobs accerelated at the bell with Weyermann and Sonia O'Sullivan
of Ireland running together with her. The race turned to a
push-and-hustle battle on the back stretch where Weyermann pushed
her way clear to lead the bunch.
</P>
<P>
Sacramento, who was still fourth off the final curve, opened a
brilliant kick on the straight for the title, while Weyermann got the
bronze with a desperate fling at the finish. O'Sullivan, former world
champion and world number one from 1994 to 1996, fated to eighth in
4:07.81. 
</P>
</TEXT>
