<HEADLINE> Cape Town Represents Africa for 2004 Olympic Bid: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
J0HANNESBURG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Cape Town is representing
Africa for the 2004 Olympic Games bid and all the continents had
hosted the Olympics except Africa, South African president Nelson
Mandela said today.
</P>
<P>
Mandela made the remarks when he was meeting with visiting
members of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Pitching Cape Town's bid for the 2004 Olympic Games, Mandela
said, many people had offered assistance in different forms, but
"your vote for the African bid would be a vote for the deepening
democracy".
</P>
<P>
He said, while he understood the difficult decision faced by
the IOC members, who had also been canvassed by other bid cities,
South Africa expected "Our friends all over the world to support
us entrench democracy".
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana said Mandela had
emphasized that South Africa had the capacity to host the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Mandela deserved a thank-you for showing the world how the
problems of a country could be solved without bloodshed or
frightening minorities, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The world owes South Africa the Olympic Games," he said.
</P>
<P>
All 20 African members of the IOC have indicated they will
vote for Cape Town's bid, the city's Bidding committee announced
last month.
</P>
<P>
The other world cities bidding to host the 2004 Olympic Game
are Greece's Athens, Brazil's Buenos Aires, Italy's Rome, and
Sweeden's Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
The IOC will meet on September 5 in Lausanne, Switzerland, to
select the winning city of the five bidders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
