<HEADLINE> Most European Shares up on Firmer Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Most stock markets in Europe
shrugged off Wall Street's opening decline and ended higher today
on a firmer dollar and solid corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
Leading shares on the London market, Europe's largest, soared
to their highest level for a fortnight, just short of their record
closing value as the FTSE 100 index jumped more than a percent to
close at 4,960.60, up 64.9 points.
</P>
<P>
Drug and oil companies led the surge, shrugging off the threat
of another rate rise later this week and boosted by strong
corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares finished the session little changed
after erasing strong early gains on the back of a sharp decline in
bond prices. The DAX-30 index closed up 5.74 points at 4,302.68.
</P>
<P>
However, French shares on the Paris bourse closed moderately
lower on continued profit-taking fuelled by expectations that US
interest rates, and possibly German rates, will rise soon. The
CAC-40 index ended the session down 8.31 points at 2,984.10.
</P>
</TEXT>
