<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Diamond Industry Enhances Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The South African diamond
industry has extended its commitment to training and development
with the expansionand re-naming of the diamond training school.
</P>
<P>
Harry Oppenheimer, former Chairman of Anglo American and De
Beers and Minister for Mineral and Energy Menuell Maduna today
officially opened the expanded school at a ceremony in
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
The school, first established in 1990 to enhance diamond
cutting skills, was renamed the Harry Oppenheimer Diamond
Training School.
</P>
<P>
The school is a partnership between De Beers and the Diamond
Foundation of South Africa, which includes the Master Diamond
Cutters' Association and the Rough Diamond Dealers' Association.
</P>
<P>
De Beers company has provided some 1639 carats of rough
diamonds for training purposes since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Oppenheimer told the opening ceremony that the expansion of
the school illustrated the commitment of De Beers to the future
of the diamond cutting industry.
</P>
<P>
The expansion was designed to open more opportunities for
those previously not involved in the industry, as well as to
upgrade diamand cutting skills and South Africa's competitiveness
in diamond trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the courses offered at the school included
six-month diamond polishing and four-week rough diamond cutting.
</P>
<P>
Future plans included the setting up of a polished grading
course in association with the Gemological Institute of America.
</P>
<P>
The school is committed to providing the most up-to-date
training and the latest equipment to the students to ensure that
the students will keep abreast with industrial advancement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Trade between Cyprus and Israel reached 70
million U.S. dollars in the first half of this year from 52
million dollars during the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement released by the Israeli Embassy here
today, the increase in trade was almost entirely caused by a
sharp rise in Israeli exports to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Imports by Cyprus from Israel, mainly pharmaceutical products
and electrical equipment, stood at more than 50 million dollars
in the January-June period, an increase of 17 million dollars
over the corresponding period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot exports to Israel, mainly leather and wood products,
totaled 19.7 million dollars in the first half of 1997,
virtually unchanged from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The total profits of 23 Kuwaiti companies
registered at the Kuwait stock market reached 158.8 million
dinars (524.0 million U.S. dollars) in the first half of this
year, up by 40 percent compared with the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
Bader Fahd Al-Humaidhi, board chairman and managing director
of the Securities Group said the whole earnings of these firms
amounted to 113.7 million dinars (375.2 million U.S. dollars)
during the first six months of 1996.
</P>
<P>
He anticipated a 60 percent rise of the companies' profits in
the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
He said share holders' returns from stock investments will be
higher than those earned from bank assets, averaging at 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Altogether 77 public sector companies have been
offered for sale by the end of June as Egypt picks up its pace of
six-year privatization, Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Ministerial Committee for Privatization under the
chairmanship of Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri Monday
reviewed the privatization program until June 1997 by which date
nearly 22 percent of the public enterprise sector had been offered
for sale.
</P>
<P>
They included 14 companies whose assets and shares were totally
sold, 43 others over half of whose shares had been sold and 20
companies with less than 50 percent of their shares being sold.
</P>
<P>
The committee also approved to sell part of the shares of other 33
state-owned companies in the field of maritime transport, industry
and trade in the Bourse in the latter half of 1997, said
Information Minister Safwat el-Sherif.
</P>
<P>
The total proceeds from selling the shares of these companies
totaled 5.88 billion Egyptian pounds (1.73 billion U.S. dollars)
of which 1.878 billion (552 million dollars) had been used to pay
debts owed to the banks.
</P>
<P>
Participation of the private sector represented 60 percent of
the volume of economic activities in Egypt by 1995, a 50 percent
rise over the 1970s. The sector is expected to shoulder 70 percent
of the investments in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
But the government has been reluctant to sell a majority stake
in vital sectors, such as oil and gas, telecommunications and
transports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
