<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Crown Prince to Visit Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 5 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan today
deputised Crown Prince Hassan to visit Israel tomorrow for talks
with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on the stalled
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The king made the decision after meeting Palestinian President
Yasser Arafat, who concluded a 2-day official visit here today,
Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
Hassan's talks with Netanyahu will focus on ways to revive
the deadlocked Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations and overcome
the obstacles facing them.
</P>
<P>
He will also discuss with Netanyahu on the recent Israeli
measures against the Palestinians following double Hamas suicide
bombings that killed 15 people last week in West Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat held talks with Hussein, Hassan and Jordanian Prime
Minister Abdul Salam Majali during his visit on the latest
developments of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The president called for international intervention to save
the peace process today at a joint press conference with Majali
before leaving Amman.
</P>
<P>
Arafat held close-door talks with Hussein on Monday. During
the talks, the king made separate telephone calls to Netanyahu,
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and the United States Secretary
of State Madleine Albright to seek for means to reactivate the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The peace process has been stalled for more than four months
since Israel declared to build Jewish settlements in Arab East
Jerusalem. On July 26, Israel decided to build new Jewish
housings in Arab neighborhood in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The peace process then took a turn for the worse after the
Jerusalem bombings as Israel exerted a security clampdown on the
Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Egypt are the only Arab countries to have reached
peace with Israel and both mediators in the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
