<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industrial Sector Remains Stimulus for Lesotho's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The industrial sector in
land-locked Lesotho remains an important stimulus for the
kingdom's economic growth, with the continuing inflow of foreign
investments, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 30 anniversary of Lesotho National Development
Corporation (LNDC) on Monday in Maseru, capital of the kingdom,
LNDC's Chief Executive Sophia Mohapi said foreign investors
continued to respond to the tiny kingdom's investment overtures.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that foreign investment to the LNDC's 21
development projects by the end of 1996 stood at 57 million Rand
(about 12.4 million US Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Mohapi said these projects had an employment potential of
6,500 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
She also said the success in the clothing and footwear sectors
would continue to act as the main source of investment into the
country.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, Mohapi stressed that the successful
development of the manufacturing sector in the kingdom would
depend on the cooperation and support of all government
ministries, the private sector and international financing
institutions in the implementation of the corporation's
objectives.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho is a small land-locked mountain country surrounded by
South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
