<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief's Visit to S. Africa Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan would not meet South African
President Nelson Mandela this week, the South African president's
office announced today.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the announcement, Mandela told reporters in Pretoria
that last night Annan and him had telephone conversation on what
he described as "sensitive matters" .
</P>
<P>
"We felt it was important that he should come here to discuss
these issues further. We will meet on Friday," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Mandela declined to say what the issues were.
</P>
<P>
Fred Eckhard, spokesman for Annan, said in New York yesterday
that an "unfortunate misunderstanding" had arisen during Anan's
telephonic conversation with Mandela earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
A poor line was apparently to blame for Mandela mistakenly
believing that Annan was coming to South Africa, Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
He added it it was understood that Jamsheet Marker, a special
representative appointed by Anan to mediate in talks between
Indonesia and Portugal to settle differences over East Timor
would meet Mandela, but no date had been set.
</P>
<P>
Marker is chairing UN-sponsored talks in New York on East
Timor to resolve the dispute between Indonesia and portugal over
the former Portuguese colony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
