<HEADLINE> Four-party Preparatory Meeting Begins in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Senior officials from China, the
United States, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
and South Korea began a preparatory meeting here today for the
four-way peace talks on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will mainly discuss procedural matters for the
four-party plenary session, including the earliest agreeable date,
venue and agenda, sources close to the meeting said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation is headed by Assistant Foreign Minister
Chen Jian, the U.S. delegation led by Charles Kartman, Principal
Deputy Assistant Secretary for East Asian and Pacific Foreign
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Heads of DPRK and South Korean delegations are Vice Foreign
Minister Kim Gye Gwan and Deputy Foreign Minister for Political
Affairs Song Young Shik.
</P>
<P>
The open-ended meeting is being held at Columbia University's
School of International and Public Affairs in New York.
</P>
<P>
The four-party peace talks were proposed in April 1996 when
U.S. President Bill Clinton visited Seoul. 
</P>
</TEXT>
