<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-05 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government Considers Upcoming Direct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government
considers the forthcoming second round of direct talks between
leaders of the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities as the
utmost importance for a Cyprus settlement, a government spokesman
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Manolis Christofides made the remarks at
his daily press briefing while commenting on the upcoming second
round of U.N.-sponsored direct talks between Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash,
scheduled to take place in Switzerland from August 11 to 16.
</P>
<P>
Christofides pointed out that "our wish and objective is to
continue these talks which we believe offer a unique opportunity
to break the deadlock and make progress toward a solution."
</P>
<P>
Referring to possible outcomes of the talks, the spokesman
said the two sides could reach a joint agreement giving the
guidelines on how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that everybody involved in this process will
seek ways to bridge the gap between the two sides, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government, he said, agrees with a U.N. suggestion
that both sides submit a draft constitution by the end of the
year, but would also like to see the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
sides submitting documents on all aspects of the Cyprus problem,
which need to be clarified.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the spokesman for the U.N. peace-keeping force in
Cyprus, Waldemar Rokoszewski, confirmed here today that the
second round of talks between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
sides will take place in the small town of Glion, near Montreux,
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
He said Clerides and Denktash will continue their talks that
began in Troutbeck, near New York, last month.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave Feissel will
leave Sunday for Geneva to attend the talks.
</P>
<P>
Foreign envoys, who were present in the first round of direct
negotiations in Troutbeck, will also be in Glion, to assist
the U.N. if and when the need arises.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite this island
nation as bi-communal, bi-zonal federation through peace talks,
but so far no tangible results have been achieved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Urges Closer Ties Among Southern African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Minister of Fisheries
Fatima Jardim today said Southern African countries, especially
the coastal countries should work out common development strategy
and strengthen bilateral cooperations.
</P>
<P>
Jardim made the remarks to newsmen after she met the visiting
Mozambican Foreign Minister Leonardo Simao.
</P>
<P>
During her talks with Simao, the Angolan minister said the two
sides agreed that Mozambique and Angola should enhance
cooperations in every field, especially in trade, mutual
investment and the exchange in developing new products.
</P>
<P>
This would benefit entrepreneurs of the two countries, she
noted.
</P>
<P>
Jardim said Angola and Mozambique have mapped out new programs
for bilateral and regional cooperation, as the economic treaty on
cooperation signed seven years ago ceased to be implemented since
the two countries were busy on its own peace process and came
across economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
She said Angolan leaders will soon contact their Mozambican
counterparts, in a bid to coordinate their policies and resume
and further promote bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Jardim stressed the importance to step up the bilateral ties
between Angola and Mozambique and the relations among the
Southern African countries, saying this would help cement the
friendship among the countries and maintain stability in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Simao arrived here Monday for a four-day visit with the aim of
strengthening the bilateral ties between Angola and Mozambique.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
