<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Than 200 Killed in  S. Korean Air Jet Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- More than 200 people were
killed today when a South Korean Air jet crashed just before
landing at the Agana International Airport in Guam.
</P>
<P>
Local police said that 29 people on board the plane survived
the crash on a hill in a rain storm at 2:35 a.m. Wednesday local
time (12:35 p.m. EDT Tuesday).
</P>
<P>
Flight 801, taking off from Seoul, South Korea, to Guam, was
cleared to land when contact was lost as the jetliner was five
kilometers from the airport, U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration's Pacific representative in Honolulu said.
</P>
<P>
The number of people on board the plane differ from different
sources. FAA officials said 331 people were on board; but airport
officials said later that 231 were aboard, and Korean Air said
there were 244 people, including about 10 crew members, were on
board the plane went down.
</P>
<P>
The airline said the plane was an Airbus, But the FAA said it
was a Boeing 747.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. National Transportation Safety Board is sending a team
from Washington to investigate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
