<HEADLINE> Europe's Role Projected for Turkish Party's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Welfare Party (RP)
leader Necmettin Erbakan today threatened that he will appeal to
the European Court of Human Rights if his party is closed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the RP parliamentary group meeting, Erbakan vowed
that no political parties legally established should be abolished
in any democratic countries.
</P>
<P>
The former prime minister said that his RP, with around 4
million members, is the biggest party in Turkey and should be by
no means neglected.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan made the remark amid the growing calls from the
certain secularist force for the closure of the RP, the senior
partner of the coalition government which resigned in June.
</P>
<P>
The Office of the Chief Prosecutor filed a case to call for RP
closure at the Constitutional Court on May 21 on the grounds of
RP's Islamic tendency.
</P>
<P>
The RP had submitted a 215-page petition containing its
preliminary defense to the court on Monday, according to local
reports.
</P>
<P>
Describing the anti-RP case as "an artificial move," Erbakan
said that the charge against his party has no legal reason.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan and his RP have long been accused by the military and
other opposition parties of conniving at the fundmentalists in the
secular republic.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Islamic politician resigned June 18 under the two fold
pressure from the military and rebelling parliamentary deputies
of the True Path Party, the junior partner of then coalition
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
