<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Sponsors Fishery Program in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) is now sponsoring a 7.7-million U.S. dollars
fishery program in Nigeria, the News Agency of Nigeria reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the program is jointly executed by the UNDP
and the Ipokia Local Government in Ogun State, southeast Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Besides providing outboard engines, storage facilities and
materials, the UNDP is also training local fishermen in fish
handling, processing, preservation, net fabrication and boat
building, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to Micheal Adeleke, the chairman of the local
government, various species of shrimps, lobsters and fishes will
be cropped in commercial quantities for export, thus reducing the
country's dependence on imported fishes.
</P>
<P>
The program will provide full employment to more than 5,000
people, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
