<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian-Japanese Relations Better than Before, Primakov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The relations between Russia and
Japan are better now than ever before, Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov told journalists on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that Moscow and Tokyo have managed to overcome the
negative aspects related to the territorial problem in their
relations.
</P>
<P>
They have agreed on the need to develop mutually-beneficial
joint economic activities in the South Kurils among other places.
</P>
<P>
Agreements on fishing remain the only difficult problem, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Practice of regular top level Russian-Japanese
consultations may become an indication of the significant
improvement of relations, Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
The development of relations with Japan and other countries of
the Asian-Pacific region is of extraordinary significance for
Russia from the view point of its geopolitical interests and the
strengthening of its role in a new, multipolar world, Primakov
noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that as for China, the key task for the two countries
this year will be "the completion of the border demarcation."
</P>
<P>
If this does not happen, the future of the border agreement
with China, which is very important for Russia, may come under
question, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He called for dropping regionalist interests hindering the
dialogue between Moscow and Beijing on border matters, or for
being guided by the need for speedy enforcement of the border
treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
