<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-05 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League: Israeli Practices Invite Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) Council said
today Israel's failure to abide by the peace agreements with the
Palestinians has invited violence to the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued at the end of an emergency meeting here
today, the AL's permanent delegates outlined a unified Arab stand
in face of Israel's "retaliatory" measures.
</P>
<P>
They categorically rejected Israeli allegations that the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) is culpable for the July 30
twin bombings in Jewish west Jerusalem that killed 13 Israeli
civilians and injured 170 others.
</P>
<P>
"Such acts are virtually the product of Israel's arrogant
stances and its non-commitment to the accords it signed with the
PNA while the latter is fully abiding by them," said the
harshly-worded communique.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government's halt of the peace process on all
tracks has escalated tension in the region, said the communique.
</P>
<P>
"Its persistence in expansionist and settlement-building
policies, usurpation of the Palestinian lands, alteration of the
demographic features of Jerusalem and demolition of the bases of
the peace process, have triggered off the current state of
affairs," the communique added.
</P>
<P>
Jewish settlers' desecration of the Muslim and Christian sacred
figures and beliefs also contributed to the tensions in the
region, it said.
</P>
<P>
The communique saw the Israeli measures tantamount to waging a
war upon the Palestinians and their leadership and requested an
immediate end of them.
</P>
<P>
Accelerating resumption of the peace process on all tracks,
reaching a fair, permanent and overall peace and a full Israeli
withdrawal from territories occupied in and after 1967, represent
the sole way out of the current stalemate and tension, it
concluded.
</P>
<P>
AL Secretary General Esmat Abdul Meguid, at a press conference
at the end of the meeting, urged an immediate action on all the
regional and international arenas to lift the embargo on the
Palestinian people imposed by Israel after last week's bombing
attacks.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting, convened a month ahead of schedule, was
called at the request of PNA President Yasser Arafat to discuss
Israel's "collective punishment" of Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The council, the supreme organ of the Arab League, may, if
necessary, hold an extraordinary session at the request of two
member states.
</P>
<P>
Following the Jerusalem bomb explosions, Israel imposed a total
closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip, canceled the planned
resumption of peace talks and halted the transfer of tax revenues
to the PNA. It has arrested 156 Palestinians suspected of terrorist
activity.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu insisted that Arafat
should launch a long-term war against anti-Israeli terrorist
organization and their infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been stalled since
mid-March when Israel began the construction of a Jewish
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
