<HEADLINE> Russian Soyuz TM-26 Launched Successfully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Soyuz TM-26 spacecraft
with Anatoly Solovyov and Pavel Vinogradov blasted off from the
Baikonur space center without a hitch today at 7:35 p.m. Moscow
time, according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
The launch was attended by Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev,
Russian Defense Council Secretary Yuri Baturin, Strategic Missile
Forces Commander Colonel-General Valery Grin and Russian Space
Forces.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass quoted a Mission Control spokesman as saying Soyuz
TM-26 has successfully entered orbit at nine minutes following the
lift-off.
</P>
<P>
The two astronauts are coming to Mir for an unprecedented
mission of repairing the orbiting space station Mir damaged on
June 25 by collision with a Progress payload craft and continuing
the research program.
</P>
<P>
They will make a spacewalk into the damaged module on August 20
to mend its disabled power circuit and examine the module's
jacket to locate the puncture.
</P>
<P>
Another sortie into the airless Spektr module is scheduled for
September 3. Solovyov and Vinogradov will inspect the module's
exterior for any possible damage before further decision-making.
</P>
<P>
Experts expect this to take up to six spacewalks.
</P>
<P>
It is not ruled out that American astronaut David Wolf, who is
to come to Mir on the Atlantis shuttle to replace Foale in late
September, will take over one or two spacewalks from Vinogradov,
to handle the problem module with Solovyov.
</P>
<P>
The National Aeronautics and space Administration has passed a
tentative decision on Wolf's part in the repairs job, with
reshuffle of Wendy Lawrence, an originally planned replacement
for Foale, for Wolf, her back-up.
</P>
<P>
Once the renewed Russian-American crew patch up the Spektr
laboratory module and restore it to operation, research will come
in the foreground.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
