<HEADLINE> Chiluba Calls for Strengthened Partnership With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba today hoped that the friendly partnership relations
between his ruling Movement for Multi-Party Democracy (MMD) and
the Communist Party of China (CPC) will be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, who doubles as MMD Chairman, said he also hoped the
friendly ties between the two countries will be reinforced
further.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with a visiting CPC delegation led by Li
Chengren, deputy head of the International Department of the CPC
Central Committee, Chiluba congratulated China on its resumption
of the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong last month, a
source from the delegation told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Ciluba said Zambia does not want to see China's territory
divided and that this is his country's stance of "one China".
</P>
<P>
He noted that the development of Hong Kong will be decided
by the Chinese people, not by others.
</P>
<P>
The president highly spoke of the gradual and systemic reforms
of China and the achievements made through these reforms.
</P>
<P>
He thanked China for its consistent support to Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The best way to strengthen the bilateral relations is to
develop partnership, work together and make profits together,
the Zambian President pointed out.
</P>
<P>
On Zambia's internal affairs, Chiluba said his government
advocates dialogue, and is opposed to violence and destruction.
</P>
<P>
In reply, Li Chengren said that under the leadership of
President Chiluba and the MMD party, Zambia has made a great
stride in safeguarding its sovereignty, maintaining national
unity, developing economy and improving people's life.
</P>
<P>
Li said the Chinese Communist Party is willing to enhance the
bilateral relations with Zambia on the basis of complete
independence, equality, mutual respect and non-interference in
the internal affairs of other parties.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, which arrived here on July 31, will leave for
Harare tomorrow to continue its visit to Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
