<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney General Criticizes Judge Confirmation Slowdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno on Tuesday criticized the Senate of an "unprecedented
slowdown" in confirming President Bill Clinton's nominees for
federal judgeships.
</P>
<P>
In prepared remarks for the American Bar Association convention
in San Francisco, Reno says the situation has reached crisis
proportions.
</P>
<P>
The national debate over who should sit on the federal bench
"has been infused with a kind of criticism that does not seek to
argue the rightness of an issue, but to undermine the very
credibility of the judiciary," news reports quoted Reno as saying.
</P>
<P>
One out of every eight federal judge positions is vacant -- 101
out of 844. Though the administration sent up 46 nominations in
1996, the Republican-dominated Senate approved only 17 U.S.
district judges and no federal appeals judges. So far this year,
the Senate has confirmed nine district judges, including three
last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Reno said the cooperation between Congress and the
administration during President Clinton's first term has been
"derailed."
</P>
<P>
She said, "We have seen an unprecedented slowdown in the Senate
confirmation machinery...At this rate it would take almost seven
years just to fill out the existing vacancies."
</P>
<P>
Reno said the impact has been felt in Illinois and Texas, and
the chief judge of the 9th U.S. Circuit has had to cancel oral
argument in 600 cases this year. The circuit includes California,
Oregon, Washington, Arizona, Nevada, Alaska, Hawaii and Montana.
</P>
<P>
The attorney general said the U.S. District Court in San Diego
"is holding only about 10 civil trials a year."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
