<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Building Permits Value Up in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The total value of building
permits rose to 5.6 billion U.S. dollars in Canada in the second
quarter, up 3.8 percent from the previous quarter, Statistics
Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was the second consecutive quarterly increase of the value
of building permits, the federal statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
Municipalities issued 3.3 billion dollars in building permits
for new housing between April and June, down 5.1 percent from the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Despite the decline, residential permits issued still represent
the second highest level of activity since the third quarter of
1994, the agency noted.
</P>
<P>
In the non-residential sector, the value of permits increased
in the first two quarters of 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the second quarter, building intentions in the
non-residential sector rose by 19.5 percent to 2.3 billion
dollars. The sector has not been this buoyant since the fourth
quarter of 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
