<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Leading Economic Indicators Unchanged in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 5 (Xinhua) -- June's Index of Leading Economic
Indicators, a main gauge to trace the U.S. economic course, held
steady at May's level of 103.8, the Conference Board reported.
</P>
<P>
This has been regarded as a weaker performance by analysts who
had forecast a 0.4 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
The unchanged performance in June followed an increase in May
of 0.3 percent and a decline in April of 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Over the six months from December 1996 to June 1997, the index
increased 1.1 percent. During the same period, seven of the 10
leading economic indicators advanced.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board said five of its 10 indicators rose in
June, with the most significant coming in stock prices and money
supply. The most significant negative contributors in June were
average weekly first-time unemployment claims and the length of
the average factory work week.
</P>
<P>
The leading index is designed to forecast economic activity six
to nine months in advance. Thus, its June performance is in line
with a widespread belief that the economy's growth has cooled
off.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
