<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Invests in Mauritania's Financial Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) today announced its first investment of 14
million U.S. dollars in Mauritania's financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The Banque Mauritanienne pour le Commerce (BMCI) will use the
credit line to lend to export-oriented companies in the western
African country.
</P>
<P>
BMCI, which is headquartered in Nouakchott, has five branches
in the main provincial centers and provides a full range of
commercial banking services with an emphasis on trade finance. Up
to date, the majority of BMCI's operations have consisted of
short-term financing projects. The IFC credit line will enable the
bank to offer longer term financing for export-oriented
enterprises and will also further develop the BMCI's trade finance
activities.
</P>
<P>
To date, IFC has invested over 15 million dollars for four
projects in Mauritania, concentrating in the agribusiness, mining,
and fishing sectors.
</P>
<P>
IFC is a member of the World Bank Group and also the largest
multilateral sources of equity and loan financing for private
sector projects in developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
