<HEADLINE> Sudan to Enact New Constitution Soon, Vice President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A new constitution will be
enacted in the war-torn Sudan within the next few days to secure
peace, according to Sudanese Vice President Al-Zubeir Mohammed
Salih today.
</P>
<P>
In a speech made to the public in Atbara, north Sudan, Salih
said the implementation of the country's 14th constitution marks
the start of the four-year interim period for south Sudan.
</P>
<P>
A council for the coordination of the south affairs, or "the
southern government," will be formed under the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The council will comprise government officials and leaders of
the four small southern rebel factions, according to the Khartoum
Peace Accord signed between the two sides last April.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, deputy speaker of the National Assembly (Sudanese
parliament) Abdul-Aziz Shedu called on John Garang, the leader of
the largest anti-government group operation in southern Sudan, the
Sudan People's Liberation Army, to join the Sudanese peace process.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a Symposium on the new constitution today, Shedu
said "Garang has no longer a cause to fight for as the problem of
the south was solved by means of the Khartoum Peace Accord and the
14th Constitution provides for the implementation of the accord."
</P>
<P>
The rebels started their fighting in 1983 for an increased
autonomy for the predominantly African, animist and Christian south
of Sudan, which is traditionally dominated by the Muslim and Arab
north. The four rebel groups that signed the peace treaty broke
away form Garang's army in the early 1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
