<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Join International Convention against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August, 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon, which used to be
labeled by the West as a "heaven of hostage takers," today took a
crucial step forward to join international efforts curbing
terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign and Emigrant Affairs Committee in the Parliament
approved a government bill to allow the country to join the
convention of countering international hostage-taking, the
official Lebanon News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The approval came six days after Washington lifted a
10-year-old ban on U.S. citizens' travel to Lebanon, imposed in
1987 after a series of kidnapings of U.S. citizens in Lebanon. But
the parliamentary committee denied any link between the two moves.
</P>
<P>
The committee's chairman, Ali Khalil, stressed that the
committee approved the bill after hearing Prime Minister Rafik
Al-Hariri's clarification that it was not under any pressure for
the government to work out the bill.
</P>
<P>
In the explanatory notes attached to the bill, the committee
emphasized that the approval didn't mean Lebanon's recognition of
Israel and Lebanon's agreement to establish any relations with the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Lebanon's adherence to the resistance in south
Lebanon against the Israeli occupation, the committee said the
convention will not affect Lebanon's stance supporting the right
of any state or people to confront and resist foreign occupation
on their lands.
</P>
<P>
The bill has to be submitted to the parliament's general
session for a vote to become effective. Local political observers
say any bill adopted by its subordinate committees is always
passed by the unicameral house without difficulties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
