<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson Rises, Zelezny Fells in Athletics Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- American Olympic hero Michael Johnson
overcame the tough time to gain his fourth world title in a row in the
men's 400 meters, while Czech men's world javelin record holder Jan
Zelezny slumped miserablely here Tuesday at the 6th World Athletics
Championships.
</P>
<P>
Johnson brought the third gold medal to the United States, which is
leading the gold medal table. Germany places second with two golds,
and the other nine top laurels were split each by as many nations.
</P>
<P>
Johnson's victory came not without a fight. The world best athlete
last year, who suffered a lot this season before the meet, lost his
dominating speed in today's final. He came off the final turn second
but somehow found some reserved strength with 50 meters to go for a
44.12-second win.
</P>
<P>
"I felt a cramp in my upper left leg at the entry to the last 100
meters. Fortunately, I got through it. After the rough season I have
had, I am glad to win and I don't want to look at the time as usually
everybody does," said the winner, whose 54 winning streak over eight
years for the 400 meters snapped last month.
</P>
<P>
Davis Kamoga of Uganda prevented an American 1-2 finish by beating
Tyree Washington in 44.37. Washington was timed in 44.39.
</P>
<P>
It was Zelezny's darkest night during his career. The three times
world champion and the outstanding world leader this year toppled
badly in the final, finishing ninth after the first three throws with
a 82.04 heave. The distance is more than 16 meters short of his world
record.
</P>
<P>
"No excuses! The day of th qualification was a good one, the day of
the final was an off one! The only problem has been my very poor
throwing technic today, " Zelezny said after the disaster.
</P>
<P>
The men's javelin gold surprisingly went to Marius Corbett of South
Africa, who flang the spear to 88.40 meters, nearly four meters longer
than his personal best.
</P>
<P>
Steve Backley of Britain, Olympic and world silver medal winner,
almost went home empty-handed. He hit the silver winning throw on the
final round at 86.80, nipping Kostas Gatsioudis, the local hero
tonight, by 20 centimeters.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Ivan Pedroso of Cuba lived up to expectation by
winning the men's long jump gold with his 8.42-meter opener. The world
indoor champion this year fouled the following four leaps before
landing a poor 7.60m jump.
</P>
<P>
Erick Walder of the United States grabbed the silver at 8.38 ahead
of Kirill Sosunov of Russia's 8.18.
</P>
<P>
"I wanted the first jump for the gold medal. Then I tried to get
the nine meters. The fourth and fifth attempts were very close, but I
slightly fouled," said a beamed Pedroso after the battle.
</P>
<P>
The day's other two finals were won by Carla Sacremento of Portugal
in the women's 1,500 meters and Sally Barsosio of Kenya in the women's
10,000 meters respectively.
</P>
<P>
Sacramento, world bronze medallist in 1995, beat Regina Jacobs of
the United States, the year's leader and hot favourite, with a
blistering kick on the home stretch to clock 4:04.24. Jacobs had to be
satisfied with the silver in 4:04.63. Anita Weyermann of Switzerland
nailed the bronze in 4:04.70. Former world great Sonia O'Sullivan of
Ireland finished eighth.
</P>
<P>
The women's 10,000m final was also a giant-killing affair which saw
Barsosio, outside of the top 10 on this year's world best list, reel
over world and Olympic champion Fernanda Ribeiro of Portugal with
three laps to go. She maintained her tempo to victory in 31:32.92.
Ribeiro wound up second in 31:39.15 and Japan's Masako Chiba finished
third in 31:41.93.
</P>
<P>
Barsosio said after her triumph:"From the beginning of the race I
planned to go away. Ribeiro has a strong kick and I didn't want to
wait for it. All the Kenyans at home will be proud of me."
</P>
<P>
Ribeiro, who only competed in the event once this year before the
meet, said:"I am happy of being second because I have been bothered by
some injuries. I tried to win but I couldn't make it. I am not
disappointed at all."
</P>
<P>
In today's qualification rounds, world famous athletes advanced to
next rounds smoothly. Five finals are slated for Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
