<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) has recently allocated 1.8 million
dollars to help improve Jordan's customs department, according to
the lastest issue of UNDP Flash.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP weekly reported that the project will modernize and
automate customs procedures through computerized systems, which
will benefit importers and exporters who have been stymied by the
lengthy and arduous clearance process.
</P>
<P>
A key part of the project is the introduction of the Automated
System for Customs Data and Management, an international standard
for customs clearance and data. The effort is a series of UNDP
projects focusing on public sector reform.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP also finalized an agreement with the Jordan government
to set up an aid coordination unit in the Ministry of Planning to
help manage overseas development assistance. 
