<HEADLINE> Armed Robberies Rampant in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Armed robberies in the west of
Nigerian commercial capital have increased over three times in
the last two weeks, apparently due to a lull in police's
crackdown operation.
</P>
<P>
The News Agency of Nigeria today quoted residents of Festac
Town, west of Lagos, as saying that two security guards were
gunned down last week by the hoodlums while two Chinese on a
trade mission were robbed thousands of U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
A police source in the town confirmed residents' accounts that
the robbers have operated unchallenged in areas where the
security guards were shot at point-blank range for refusing to
open the gates.
</P>
<P>
Many of the robberies were so easily carried out that some
residents believed that the burglars could be living within the
town as they "knew exactly where police patrols are and their
modus operandi" before they struck.
</P>
<P>
Police, however, attributed their inability to deal with the
increasing armed robbery cases to inadequate telephone facilities
and fewer police vehicles deployed in the area.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted sources as saying that the relocation of
some well-to-do retired military and civil servants as well as
prosperous businessmen to the area and the intensification of
security patrols in other parts of Lagos have forced some of the
armed robbers to shift base to areas they consider safe.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of two helicopters two weeks ago to the police
to fight crime in the state has made it harder for criminals to
operate with impunity as they used to in broad day light in some
of the city's business districts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
