<HEADLINE> UNDP Helps Ecuador, Peru, Poland Control Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) has allocated 632,900 dollars to help
Ecuador and Peru lessen the most serious effects of El Nino, a
disastrous climatic condition, according to the UNDP.
</P>
<P>
El Nino, which in past years has caused severe flooding,
droughts, avalanches and mudslides in parts of Latin America,
could affect over 8 million people in Peru and Ecuador in 1997,
according to recent forecasts.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP's assistance will be mainly used to strengthen the
governments' ability to plan preventive measures and respond to
natural disasters, and will make improved satellite images and
weather maps available.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP and the UN Department of Humanitarian Affairs are also
helping Poland respond to the worst flooding in Central Europe
this century, which has forced evacuation of 140,000 people, left
50,000 homeless and severely damaged infrastructure, agriculture
and industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
