<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe, S. Africa Seal Trade Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe and South Africa signed
here today the awaited trade agreement on satisfactory quota and
preferences for agricultural products in the ongoing negotiations
between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
the accord, which was expected to increase Zimbabwe's trade
volumes to South Africa, however, excluded certain veterinary and
photosanitary issues.
</P>
<P>
Signed by Zimbabwean and South African ministers of industry
and commerce Nathan Shamuyarira and Alexander Erwin respectively,
the pact meant that virtually all products that were covered in
the 1964 agreement had been dealt with and preference margins
reinstated.
</P>
<P>
The products include beef, cereals, dairy products and
poultry.
</P>
<P>
Up to 5,000 tons of beef, 1,000 tons of poultry meat and live
pigs are expected to be exported to South Africa duty free.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is expected to boost agricultural exports to
South Africa by 44 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
In order to strengthen and expand the trade accord, the two
ministers proposed to establish a trade and investment committee
which they would chair together.
</P>
<P>
The committee would monitor current arrangements and review
them when necessary.
</P>
<P>
It would deal with further trade liberalization, both
bilateral and in the context of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) protocol, and promote trade through private
sector participation.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it would promote trade through harmonization of
all trade related measures and standards, promote investment
through conferences, cooperation by development corporations and
facilitating investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
