that Athens had requested clarification from Ankara over the
accuracy of Yilmaz's statements.
</P>
<P>
If Yilmaz was quoted accurately in the U.S. newspaper, his
claim undermined the spirit of the Madrid communique and supported
a claim that was entirely illogical, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Yilmaz's statements do not contribute to the efforts to
improve Greek-Turkish relations," he added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that relations between the two countries must be
governed by international law and international treaties.
</P>
<P>
The joint communique, which was signed between Turkish
President Suleyman Demirel and Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
while attending the NATO summit in Madrid, called for respect for
the sovereignty of each country, international law and treaties as
well as resolution of disputes through peaceful means. 
