<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US President Signs Balanced Budget, Tax Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
signed into law today balanced federal budget and tax breaks bills
designed to balance the U.S. budget by 2002.
</P>
<P>
The legislation calls for balancing the federal budget in five
years by cutting government spending by about 130 billion dollars.
The tax bill will trim taxes by 152 billion dollars over five
years, the largest tax cut in the U.S. since 1981.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony held in South Lawn of the White House,
Clinton hailed the new laws as "a true milestone for our nation."
</P>
<P>
The balanced-budget bill is designed to eliminate deficits for
the first time since 1969. It calls for about 130 billion dollars
in spending restraints, much of it from squeezing payments to
doctors and hospitals in the giant Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
The tax bill features a 500-dollar-per-child credit for
families; a reduction in the capital-gains tax and roughly 35
billion dollars in benefits for students that Clinton wanted.
</P>
<P>
Details of the measures approved today now must be written into
13 appropriations bills that the U.S. Congress must pass for
Clinton to sign.
</P>
<P>
The balanced-budget and tax agreement was reached only when the
U.S. government and Republican-controlled Congress abandoned their
political grudges early this year, aided by a booming economy that
produced higher government revenues than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
In the fierce struggle between the two U.S. parties in 1995 and
1996, President Clinton twice vetoed Republican balanced budget
bills, leading to two partial government shutdowns in the winter
of 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
U.S. House Speaker Newt Gingrich attended the ceremony and said
that he doesn't intend to abandon the spirit of cooperation that
led to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
But House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, an opponent of the
pack, did not attend today's signing. In a letter, he urged
Clinton to use his line item veto authority to strike a provision
of the law that allows tobacco companies to deduct the proposed
cigarette tax increase from the proposed tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
Under the tax bill signed today, the current 24-cent-a-pack
federal tax on cigarettes will increase by 10 cents in 2000 and by
another nickel in 2002. That will raise 5.2 billion dollars over
five years and 16.7 billion over 10 years for the government
revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
