<HEADLINE> Auto Makers Invest 1.3 Billion Dollars in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Auto makers invested a total of
1.3 billion U.S. dollars in Canada in the first six months of
1997, placing it in fifth place worldwide for the period, a report
said today.
</P>
<P>
The United States led all countries, with 2.8 billion dollars
invested by vehicle assembly companies.
</P>
<P>
Brazil placed second, with 1.9 billion dollars, according to a
study released by the Canadian Automotive Parts Manufacturers'
Association.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Poland ranked third and fourth, with an investment
of 1.5 billion and 1.4 billion dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Canada was in eight position when the study was first
conducted, for a period that covered 18 months ended December 31,
1996, the Financial Post newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Since then, auto investment levels have dropped in many
emerging markets, including India, China, Argentina and Russia,
all of which ranked ahead of Canada in the first survey.
</P>
<P>
Worldwide, auto makers committed 15.3 billion dollars for
capital expenditure in the first six months of this year, the
study said. 
</P>
