<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Vows Fight Against British Rule to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Gerry Adams, leader of Sinn Fein,
the political wing of the Irish Republican Army (IRA), said today
that his party would maintain its objective of ending British rule
in Northern Ireland during next month's multi-party peace talks on
the region's future.
</P>
<P>
"Sinn Fein enters negotiations as an Irish Republican party
seeking to promote the broad nationalist objective of an end to
British rule in Ireland," Adams said in his first meeting with
Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam in Belfast since
the IRA declared a ceasefire on July 20.
</P>
<P>
"We want an Ireland free and independent," media reports quoted
Adams as saying while the talks were underway.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein had been barred from negotiations on Northern Ireland
between officials from Britain, Ireland and the United States'
mediator because of the IRA's refusal to renounce violence in its
struggle against British rule in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,200 people have been killed in the fighting over
the past 28 years.
</P>
<P>
The Sinn Fein leader also appealed to the pro-British unionist
parties not to walk out of the talks when they resume in the
second week of September.
</P>
<P>
The unionist parties in Northern Ireland insist that Sinn Fein
be excluded from the multi-party peace talks until the IRA
surrenders its weapons.
</P>
<P>
"Sinn Fein wants to see the unionist parties at the negotiating
table in September... Unionists are an intrinsic part of
Ireland. This is your home," Adams said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Labor government to adopt the role of "a
persuader" to convince Unionists that their future inevitably lies
in a united Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
