<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholars Refute US Report on Religion (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Members of China's religious
community and scholars today expressed indignation over a recent US
State Dept. report on religion which included unfounded
accusations on the religious situation in China.
</P>
<P>
The US report represents a gross interference in China's
internal affairs, according to members of the religious community
and scholars attending a forum sponsored by the Religion Research
Center in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Shi Zesheng, vice-chairman of the Three-Self Patriotic
Movement Committee of Protestant Churches in China, pointed out
that China's Constitution and related laws guarantee Chinese
citizens full freedom of religious belief, and protect the
activities of religious organizations nationwide.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that some people flaunt the banner of
religion and disrupt public security by resorting to demagogy to
engage in seducing female followers.
</P>
<P>
He added the United States has itself cracked down on similar
illegal activities, with the most notable case centering on the
all-out assault on the Branch Davidians some two years ago.
</P>
<P>
According to Shi, some people in the United States cited China's
punishment of law violators as "interference in religious freedom"
and 'cracking down on religious groups'.
</P>
<P>
He said that in doing so, these people deliberately confused
right from wrong and represented nothing more than blasphemy of
sacred religious belief.
</P>
<P>
In a written speech at the forum, Doctor Han Wenzao, president
of the China Christian Council, said that he was shocked that the
US State Deptment would release such an unfactual report.
</P>
<P>
Facts show that there is religious freedom in China, Han said.
</P>
<P>
More than 12,000 Protestant churches and 25,000 religious
venues have reopened in China since 1979. Today there are over 17
Protestant seminaries, compared to only one prior to the Cultural
Revolution (1966-1976).
</P>
<P>
Han pointed out that Xu Yongze, the subject of the report,
wantonly preached that "the end of the world is coming
soon," and incited followers to engage in extended sessions
of wailing. Xu's activities seriously affected the normal life
and work of his followers, with a number of people later diagnosed
as schizophrenic.
</P>
<P>
"Xu's activities deviated from the true teachings of the
Sculpture and the truth of Christianity, and he has been detained
for illegal activities in accordance with normal legal procedures
in China. Xu's detention can in no way be compared to
so-called 'religious persecution," said Han.
</P>
</TEXT>
