<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholars Refute US Report on Religion (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bishop Ding Guangxun, president of the China Christian Council,
said that the US report "fully demonstrates that the United States
considers itself as the world police and global leader.
</P>
<P>
"I did not hope that the US advisory committee on overseas
religious freedom will become a tool enabling the US State
Department to engage in overseas intervention."
</P>
<P>
Ding also serves as honorary chairman of the Three-Self
Patriotic Movement Committee of the Protestant Churches of China,
an self-supporting organization in terms of both administration
and propagation.
</P>
<P>
The US report blatantly attacks China for "controlling churches"
and "denying the Vatican the authority to appoint bishops."
</P>
<P>
However, Fu Tieshan, vice-chairman of the Chinese Catholic
Bishops College, refuted the argument on historical facts.
</P>
<P>
Fu noted that 29 Chinese bishops, or 21 percent of the total
number of bishops nationwide, served in 137 parishes during
semi-feudal and semi-colonial periods in old China. He also
pointed out that only three of 20 archbishops were Chinese.
</P>
<P>
All colonial characteristics of Chinese Catholicism ended with
liberation. China currently has 115 parishes led by Chinese
bishops and parish priests.
</P>
<P>
The parishes have made a conscientious effort to nurture
more than 900 young and capable priests.
</P>
<P>
Every year, the nation's Catholic churches host more
than 100,000 priests and religious believers from some 90
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Chinese bishops, priests and believers in Old China were seldom
invited to participate in foreign exchanges or international
conferences.
</P>
<P>
Over the past ten-plus years, however, members of the Chinese
Catholic community have visited 20 countries and regions,
including Belgium, Germany and the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
