<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholars Refute US Report on Religion (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jing Hui, vice-president of the Buddhist Association. of China
who has lived in temples for decades, outlined freedom of
religious belief in China based on his personal experience.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, Jing has been in charge of reconstructing the
Bailin Monastery belonging to the Dhyana Buddhist Sect. According
to Jing, the monastery performs large-scale meditation and sutra
recitation services at least four times per year, with hundreds
to thousands of devout believers attending each session.
</P>
<P>
The monastery has organized summer camps for young Buddhists on
an annual basis since 1993, with each camp attracting as many as
200 participants, including a number of young people from
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
All these activities are organized and managed by local
Buddhists and are free from any outside interference.
</P>
<P>
With reference to the US report's support of the 14th Dalai
Lama, Jing Hui and Jiamyang Tubdan, abbot of the Yonghe Lamasery
in Beijing and executive council member of the Buddhist
Association of China, pointed out that the 14th Dalai Lama has
alienated himself from the vast majority of Tibetan Buddhists.
</P>
<P>
The 14th Dalai Lama has abandoned the fine tradition of loyalty
to the motherland established by his predecessors, and has instead
opted to establish a government in exile, engage in activities to
split the motherland, violate all historical conventions and
sabotage the search for the reincarnated soul boy of the 10th
Panchen Lama, and disrupt the internal unity and precepts of
Tibetan Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
Jiamyan Tubdan asked why Buddhist believers should have
any trust in the 14th Dalai Lama, a harbinger of disaster to his
country and Tibetan Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the United States has acted as a mouthpiece
to air the grievances of the Dalai Lama clearly indicates the
backing he receives from foreign forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
