<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholars Refute US Report on Religion (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Min Zhiting, vice-president of the China Taoist Association,
said the Constitution stipulates religious freedom for all
Chinese. No government department, mass organization or individual
may force a Chinese citizen to either believe or disbelieve in
religion, nor are they allowed to discriminate against citizens
believing and not believing in religions.
</P>
<P>
"Constitutional protection has enabled Taoism to enjoy New
China's religious freedom which is totally free of
discrimination," said Min.
</P>
<P>
He added that China is currently home to 4,105 Taoist temples,
as well as 15 Taoist associations at the provincial level and 108
associations at the county level.
</P>
<P>
Taoists are playing their role in the political arena by
serving as deputies to people's congresses and members of Chinese
people's political consultative conferences.
</P>
<P>
He said: "The US report totally distorts the actual religious
situation in China."
</P>
<P>
Haji Shamsiddin Mahmud, vice-president of the China Islamic
Association, refuted allegations that China is restricting the
religious freedom of ethnic minorities."
</P>
<P>
Mahmud pointed out that the Constitution guarantees the right
to religious freedom for all Chines citizens, and he stressed that
the Chinese government has paid special attention to protecting
the legitimate rights and interests of Muslims.
</P>
<P>
For example, the government has granted Muslims the right to
burial rather than cremation, protected their traditional
lifestyles, and severely punished those defiling their religious
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
Mahmud said the government has provided convenient passport
certification, foreign currency exchange and transportation enabling
large numbers of Muslims to take pilgrimages to Mecca, and travel
to other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
More than 45,000 Muslims have undertaken paid pilgrimages and
engaged in religious studies in other countries, said Min.
</P>
</TEXT>
