<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholars Refute US Report on Religion (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wu Yungui, director of the Religious Research Institute under
the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, and Zhao Kuangwei,
director of the Religion Research Center, maintained that it is
beyond the realm of common sense that the US report claims that
the Chinese government restricts freedom of religion and
persecutes religion.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that the Chinese Communist Party has
been unswervingly pursuing the policy on religious freedom,
and respecting both religions and religious believers.
</P>
<P>
The Constitution stipulates religious freedom as a basic right
for all Chinese citizens, with detailed clauses on protection
contained in the Criminal Law, General Rules on Civil Law, Law on
Regional Autonomy, Military Service Law, Compulsory Education Law,
Election Law and Village Committee Organization Law.
</P>
<P>
Wu and Zhao joined in stressing that not a single person in
China has been imprisoned or arrested for their religious beliefs,
and that all citizens are equal before the law, regardless of
their religious preferences.
</P>
<P>
People the US report cited as being involved in so-called
"religious persecution" cases were, in fact, criminals and
punishment of criminals has nothing to do with religious beliefs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholars Refute Report on Religion (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ma Yuhong, a researcher with the Religions Research Center,
repudiated the wanton distortions the US report placed on China's
registration of religious venues.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that countries around the world have adopted the
common practice of requiring mass organizations to register with
the government.
</P>
<P>
For example, Japan has passed a law governing legal religious
representatives, and religious organizations in the US are
required to register with the government for tax exemptions.
</P>
<P>
Religious organizations in China, just as any other mass
organization, are required to register with the Civil affairs
departments.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 religious organizations have registered with
the government, and some 80,000 religious venues have been granted
registration certificates over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
Registered venues enjoy better legal protection in accordance
with China's laws and regulations. This in no way involves
"controlling religions", according to Ma.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the US State Department accusation that the
Chinese government shuts down family churches is totally
irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
In fact, there are no so-called "family churches" in
China. Chinese refer to Christian customs such as relatives,
friends and family members gathering in a private residence to
engage in prayer and the recitation of scriptures as a "family
get-together."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has never interfered with the
aforementioned family gatherings, which are instead highly
respected and not subject to registration. Therefore, the
aforementioned accusation is totally groundless.
</P>
<P>
Also addressing the forum were members of the Beijing's
religious community and organizations, as well as scholars from
the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, Beijing University,
Central University for Ethnic Minorities and the Religion
Research Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
