<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Poll Body Asked to Explain Decision on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Supreme Court today
required the Commission on Elections (Comelec) to explain its
earlier decision to dismiss a plea by a private group to verify
the signatures gathered for changing the constitution.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution, the court gave the poll body a non-extendible
period of 10 days to explain why to reject the six million
signatures gathered by the People's Initiative for Reform,
Modernization and Action (PIRMA) for the purpose of amending the
charter.
</P>
<P>
The PIRMA, created by Ramos' supporters in late 1996, has
sought to rewrite the country's 1987 constitution to lift term
limits of all elective government officials including President
Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
The high tribunal made the decision after the PIRMA filed a
petition seeking an order from the court directing the Comelec to
act on the signatures. But the court did not require the poll body
to act on the signatures the PIRMA submitted to it in June.
</P>
<P>
The Comelec rejected the signatures last month on the ground
that the Supreme Court had already issued a ruling in March
banning any initiative for charter change because of the lack of
such enabling law in the country.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here said it seemed that the Supreme Court
is changing its mind to give the PIRMA a chance since today's
ruling is conflicting its earlier ban which also requires the
PIRMA to stop collecting signatures.
</P>
<P>
According to Clerk of Court Luzviminda Puno, the high tribunal
has to wait for the comment of the Comelec before it can decide
whether to require the poll body to act on the signatures.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1987 constitution, the Philippine president can serve
only one single six-year term.
</P>
<P>
Ramos has vowed on many occasions that he will step down when
his term of office expires in June 1998. But he also insisted
that the people have the right to change the constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
