<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Stands Firm on Punitive Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today stood firm on continuing the punitive
measures taken against the Palestinians following last week's
suicide bombings in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference after his talks with
visiting Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan, Netanyahu said the
measures were necessary to protect Israel's security as long as
the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) refused to commit
itself to fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu held talks here with Hassan and Jordanian Prime
Minister Abdul-Salam Majali to discuss the heightened
Israeli-Palestinian crisis in the aftermath of the double
bombings in Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda market last Wednesday,
which killed 15 people and wounded 170 others.
</P>
<P>
No apparent results were achieved in the talks, in which the
Jordanian side tried to persuade Netanyahu to ease the tough
measures taken against the PNA, including a total closure on the
territories, travel ban on Palestinians, expelling Palestinian
workers and halting transfer of tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
"We know that this campaign of terror must be stopped before
to have peace. If we have to say what is the indispensable step
to saving peace, peace between us and Palestinians, it is for
the Palestinian Authority to take firm, excessive, comprehensive
and immediate steps against the infrastructure of the terrorist
organizations," Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
The hardline Israeli leader pinpointed the Israeli concern
that the PNA's failure to fight terror would not only undermine
the ability to apprehend those behind the recent suicide
bombings, but also increase difficulty in preventing future
attacks.
</P>
<P>
"Preventing such attacks should be the interest of the
Palestinian Authority, as is ours, and certainly their solemn
obligation to fight terrorism. This is the heart and, indeed,
main principle of the Oslo accords," he said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu reiterated that the tough measures taken by Israel
were not directed at the Palestinian people, but aimed at
protecting Israel's security. He noted that Israel allowed the
transfer of food and medicines on humanitary grounds.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Prince Hassan said Jordan was committed to the
concept of "no peace without security, and no security without
peace." Warning the situation was on verge of dangerous crisis,
he expressed the hope that security cooperation between Israel
and the PNA would be resumed.
</P>
<P>
While expressing understanding about Israel's security
concerns, Hassan called on Israel to ease the tough measures
against the Palestinians in order to make a "human peace."
</P>
<P>
"I would like to say very clearly that we are dealing here
with a human peace, a peace that affects life, promotes life and
promote human dignity, and in particular the parity of people,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Hassan hoped that the ongoing mediation efforts by Jordan,
Egypt, European Union (EU) and the United States could bring the
peace process back on track in the next few months. He stressed
that this was the right response to extremism and violence.
</P>
<P>
Hassan's visit was part of a flurry of intensive diplomatic
efforts aimed at easing the rising tension between Israel and
the Palestinian side and reviving the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of last week's terror attack, the U.S., EU, Egypt
and Jordan launched a diplomatic campaign to try to save the
ill-fated Israeli-Palestinian peace process from collapse.
</P>
<P>
But in a sign of difference, Hassan came here in stead of
King Hussein, who canceled his trip here for fear about the
lack of substantial results from his talks with Netanyahu, who
reportedly has been invited to visit Amman next week for further
consultations.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Jordanian and Israeli leaders also came
ahead of arrival here this weekend of U.S. peace envoy Dennis
Ross, who is expected to initiate a new round of mediation to
get the derailed Israeli-Palestinian peace process back on
track. 
</P>
</TEXT>
