<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Development of Cooperative Share-holding Firms in Cities Suggested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- China will pay greater attention
to the development of cooperative share-holding enterprises in
cities.
</P>
<P>
A document, which was recently issued by the State Commission
for Restructuring Economic System under the State Council, noted
that the development of such enterprises in cities will suit the
needs of a socialist market economy and help promote the
development of productive forces.
</P>
<P>
The document with the title of "Guiding Comments on the
Development of Cooperative Share-holding Enterprises in Cities"
said that based on experience in the rural reform of the country,
many cities have established cooperative share-holding firms and
the establishment of such enterprises has reinvigorated a large
number of small companies.
</P>
<P>
The document terms the kind of enterprises a new form for
collectively-owned economic entities, which combines labor
cooperation with capital cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The system is in conformity with the present situation for
state-owned small companies and collectively-owned firms and it
meets the demands of the modern enterprise system with the
characters of having a clear property right, being clear in rights
and obligations for all parties involved, separation of government
functions from enterprises, and operating scientifically, the
document said.
</P>
<P>
In such a company, it said, the staff and workers work
together, jointly own and utilize the production means, share weal
and woe, and conduct democratic management and administration.
</P>
<P>
It suggested that shares held by staff members and the
collectives should account for the lion's share of the total
capital in these firms, and, meanwhile, part of the shares could
be held by the state and legal persons.
</P>
<P>
The setting-up of this kind of firms could play a positive role
in developing local economy, increasing financial income for local
governments, creating new employment opportunities and maintaining
social stability, the document stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Boss Threatens to Expel Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Fifa president Joao
Havelange threatened on Wednesday that Brazil would be expelled
from the world soccer's governing body and from the World Cup if a
bill drawn up by Brazilian sports minister Pele becomes law.
</P>
<P>
Havelange said in an interview with the Jornal do Brasil daily
that there would be no alternative if the bill was approved.
</P>
<P>
"The Fifa committees will have a meeting and expel Brazil, who
will not be able to take part in the World Cup as a result, " he
said.
</P>
<P>
Pele's new bill, presented to President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso on Tuesday, proposes incentives for clubs that become
publicly traded companies, making soccer club directors more
accountable and to turning all players into free agents within two
years.
</P>
<P>
It also proposes taking control of disciplinary tribunals and
refereeing away from the Brazilian Football Confederation (CBF)
and handing them to independent bodies.
</P>
<P>
"Fifa statutes say that referees have to be subordinated to the
(national) associations, just as do disciplinary tribunals,"
Havelange said.
</P>
<P>
"The CBF has been a member of Fifa for more than 80 years,
always respecting its statutes and rules. It's the same with all
the other affiliated associations. Anyone who does not agree can
leave. But they won't get a game.
</P>
<P>
"It's strange that the (sports) ministry should turn against an
institution that is being run in an efficient and modern way," he
was quoted as saying, referring to the CBF. "I'm respected in the
entire world and now I see the government of my country turning
against the entity (over) which I preside." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister: Iraq Expects Resumption of Oil Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraq announced today it will
resume its oil exports after the U.N.'s approval of its new oil
pricing list in a few days.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed Rasheed made the announcement
at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
Rasheed said that Iraq sent an oil pricing list Tuesday to the
U.N. Sanctions Committee for approval, adding that Iraq expects the
approval in a few days.
</P>
<P>
After the approval, the Iraqi Oil Ministry can sign contracts
with world companies willing to import Iraqi oil.
</P>
<P>
Rasheed expected the exportation of Iraqi oil to resume within
a week or 10 days via the Iraqi port of Al-Bakr and the Turkish
port of Ceyhan.
</P>
<P>
The minister pointed out that Iraq's oil production capacity is
capable of meeting its exporting quota for the second six-month
period of the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Iraq signed the oil-for-food deal with the U.N. in May last
year. The deal went into effect in last December, allowing Iraq to
export 2 billion U.S. dollars of oil to buy food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The deal was renewed by the U.N. on June 8, allowing Iraq to
export another 2 billion dollars of oil.
</P>
<P>
Rasheed added that Iraq is ready to pump out its oil across the
Iraqi-Syrian pipeline as soon as it gets Syria's approval, and
that it will carry out the natural gas project agreed upon with
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Iraq had stopped exporting its oil for the second stage of the
oil-for-food deal pending the U.N. chief's approval of Iraq's new
food distribution plan. The plan was endorsed by U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
