<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, U.S. Aviation Meeting Fruitless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A three-day Japanese-U.S. aviation
meeting closed today with no accord reached as the two sides
failed to narrow their differences over measures to liberalize
trans-Pacific flight services.
</P>
<P>
"The two countries remained wide apart over important issues,"
Hiromichi Toya, Japanese vice transport minister who headed the
Tokyo negotiating team, told a press conference after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Alan Larson said, "Although
we developed some bracketed text on certain issues, the two sides
are still far apart."
</P>
<P>
At the vice ministerial meeting, the U.S. renewed its demand
for an "open skies" pact with Japan for full liberalization of the
aviation market between the two countries, Kyodo news service said.
</P>
<P>
Japan rejected the U.S. request but presented its own phased-in
deregulation measures and asked Washington to rectify the 1952
civil aviation treaty which Japan sees as unfairly benefiting
U.S. carriers.
</P>
<P>
Under that treaty, three U.S. carriers -- Northeast Airlines,
United Airlines and Federal Express -- are allowed to expand
flights and add new routes, while only one Japanese carrier, Japan
Airlines, enjoys the same privileges in the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The two sides will meet again in Washington on August 27-29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
