<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania, Greece Discuss Closer Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Some 350,000 Albanian refugees in
Greece may be allowed to live and work in the country for up to 12
months under a deal signed today between the two neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by visiting Greek Foreign Minister
Theodoros Pangalos and his Albanian counterpart Paskal Milo,
allows for 350,000 Albanian refugees to get "green cards,"
allowing them to work in Greece for between six and 12 months.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos, who arrived here for visit, has met Albanian
officials to discuss cooperation over border issues, combatting
Albanian organized crime and the education of ethnic Greeks
in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Greece will also help Albania rearm its troops and police by
providing a loan of 20 million U.S. dollars to the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
The Greek minister promised to table the matter of Albania's
entry into the European Union at the forthcoming EU foreign
minister meeting.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos' visit, the first by a senior Greek minister since
the new Albanian government was formed 10 days ago, is seen as an
important step forward in relations between the two nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Population Tops 82 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The number of people living in Germany
has topped 82 million for the first time in history, exclusively due
to immigrations, the German Federal Office of Statistics said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Wiesbaden-based agency, German population rose
0.2 percent from the level of 1995 to reach 82.012 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
As was the case in the past several years, the number of births in
Germany last year once again ran below the number of deaths with a
difference of 87,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of people immigrated to Germany dropped
from 800,000 in 1995 to 700,000 in 1996, 178,000 of them were ethnic
Germans from eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Last year also saw much less Germans move from the eastern part of
the country to the western half when compared with the figures
registered immediately after the German reunification in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Separately, according to an expert of the German Federal
Institute for Population Research, Evelyn Gruenheid, the number of
Germans over 90 years old could reach nearly one million up to the
year 2040.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the average life expectancies are nearly 80 years for
the female newborns and 73 years for the male in Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0115 </DOCNO>
