<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African Culture, Development Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A three-day southern African
conference on culture and development opened here today, with
over 50 delegates from the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) states to discuss relations between culture and economic
development.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Vice-Chancellor of University of
Zimbabwe Graham Hill said the impact of Africa's colonial legacy
on culture and the drive towards economic and cultural
globalization made it imperative for the SADC states to assume a
common cultural stance.
</P>
<P>
Southern Africa's drive towards economic development cannot be
achieved unless the countries, as stakeholders in the global
village, assume a common cultural stance, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that southern African countries should study their own
cultures rather than wait for outside motivation.
</P>
<P>
Africa could not attain its goals without putting the cultures
of its people, the beneficiaries of development, at center stage,
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Hill said, "when the cultures of the people at the grassroots
of African societies take the center stage of social
transformation, only then will it be possible to genuinely
improve the quality of lives of many people." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
