<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dry-up of Lower Reaches of Yellow River Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhengzhou, August 6 (Xinhua) -- After a 132-day dry-up, the
lower reaches of the yellow river had water flow again this
morning, bringing hope to the weathering crops there.
</P>
<P>
Lijin Hydrographic Station at the end of the lower reaches of
the yellow river had water running through it at 7:18 this
morning. By 8:00 am, the rate of water flow reached 510 cubic
metres per second.
</P>
<P>
Experts with the water conservancy Commission of Yellow River
said that the dry spell in the middle and lower reaches of the
river was disrupted by torrential rains that hit the provinces of
Shanxi, Shaanxi, and Henan from July 28 to 31.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains resulted in flood peaks to Huayuankuo Hydrographic
Station at the mouth of the lower reaches of the yellow river on
August 4, with a flow rate of 4,020 cubic metres per second.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River which cuts through seven provinces in
northwest China has suffered frequent dry-ups since 1990 due to
reduced rainfalls and rapid growth in the use of water for
industrial and agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
This year's dry-up started in February, earlier than usual and
its dry-up length is the longest in history.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Promote Distance Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government will
soon sign a charter to promote distance education in the country,
Higher Education and Technology Minister Ignatius Chombo said
today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a distance education librarianship seminar at the
Sesa Training Center, Chombo said the charter will pave the way
for the establishment of a open learning distance education
center.
</P>
<P>
The success of distance education programs in any country
depended on librarians, Chombo added.
</P>
<P>
"In the next three months, we are going to start eight-degree
programs for distance education at the newly established open
learning distance center," said Chombo.
</P>
<P>
He said, "there is need for versatile librarians in Zimbabwe
whose work will determine the success of these proposed distance
education programs."
</P>
<P>
The one-day seminar, attended by some 25 librarians from
Lesotho, Swaziland, Malawi, South Africa and Zimbabwe, was
organized by the Zimbabwe Library Association and the
Commonwealth Library Association
</P>
<P>
Chombo said that seminars used to formulate new strategies
would get Commonwealth governments to speed up and sensitize
education administrators about the importance of providing
regulatory and infrastructural framework appropriate for building
up platforms for libraries for distance education.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out, "Education is a basic right to all human
beings, but not all people get the privilege to pursue formal
classroom education either for the basic education or
professional enhancement."
</P>
<P>
"Libraries and librarians are pivotal to formal education and
are even the backbone for distance education as they match and
bridge documented information and the consumers," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
