<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Star-Studded Field Expected for Hong Kong Squash Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is to host one of
this year's most important squash tournaments later this month,
organizers announced here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific Squash Open '97 is slated for August 24-31 in
the Hong Kong Squash Center and the Hong Kong Park Indoor Games
Hall, with a record entry of 23 players out of the world's top 23.
</P>
<P>
World champion and seven-time winner of the Hong Kong Open
Jansher Khan from Pakistan will return to gain revenge over
defending champion world number three Rodney Eyles of Australia.
</P>
<P>
Rodney upset the form book with a convincing straight-games win
over Jansher in last year's Hong Kong Open.
</P>
<P>
Up-and-coming star and local favorite, Scotland's Peter Nicol,
has improved greatly with his world ranking rising to number
two. He beat Jansher 3-1 in the final of the Al-Ahram
International in Egypt in June.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Shum, a former ace player of Hong Kong, will return to
this year's Open after being absent from the tournament for at
least two years. Having aimed at next year's Asian Games in
Bangkok, he is keen to represent the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR), Shum is favored to pass the
qualifying round.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's Faheem Khan, ranked 45th in the world, has obtained
 a wild card to spearhead the HKSAR side in the challenge in the
main draw. But he will first play in the World Games and
Singapore Open before coming back for the Hong Kong event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
