<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Wins Software Piracy Compensation in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- An Australian computer company
has been ordered to pay nearly 1.5 million US dollars in damages
after importing and supplying fake copies of Microsoft software
programs, the Australian Associated Press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The company, CT Group (Australia) Pty Ltd, sold about 21,500
fake copies of Microsoft's MS-DOS and Windows operating systems,
the Australian Associated Press quoted documents produced by
Microsoft in a court as reporting.
</P>
<P>
Justice James Burchett ordered on Tuesday CT group to pay
Microsoft 1.43 million U.S. dollars in damages for breaches of the
Copyright Act, plus 88,800 dollars of interest.
</P>
<P>
Ron Eckstrom, Microsoft Corporation's Asia Pacific region
corporate attorney, said in a statement issued today that the
award was the largest software copyright infringement judgment yet
made in Australia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
