<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Government Secretary Meets With Sinn Fein Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Northern Ireland
Secretary Mo Mowlam began her first face-to-face meeting today
with Gerry Adams, president of the IRA's political wing Sinn Fein,
to discuss peace process in the divided province.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place in Belfast less than three weeks after
Irish Republican Army, a guerrilla group aiming to end the British
rule of Northern Ireland, called a ceasefire on July 20.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam is expected to tell Adams that Sinn Fein will be allowed
to take part in multi-party peace talks in September for the first
time if the British government judges that the IRA ceasefire is
deemed genuine and credible.
</P>
<P>
There have been no IRA bomb or gun attacks since the guerrillas
called the truce last month in a bid to get Sinn Fein to the
negotiating table for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam is also expected to tell Adams that Northern Ireland
will remain part of Britain so long as the majority, which is
currently 60 percent pro-British Protestant, wants it to be and
that nothing will alter that, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
Adams told reporters before the talks began that he has been
trying to join the all-party peace talks since 1993 and Sinn Fein
should have been in talks with the British government "a long time
ago".
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein was barred from the talks by Britain and Ireland,
co-sponsors of the negotiations, and cast into the political
wilderness until the July 20 IRA truce to its 28-year war which
has cost lives of about 3,200 people.
</P>
<P>
Adams' meeting with Mowlam will mark a step towards ending his
vilification by successive British governments who banned his
voice from the airwaves and barred him from Britain until the
first IRA truce in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
