<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Puerto Rico Wins Again in Under-23 Basketball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Puerto Rico, stunned by
under-rated New Zealand in the first half, fought back to maintain
its unbeaten run with an 11 point victory in the men's Under-23
World Basketball Championship in Melbourne on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand led 39-35 at halftime before the Puerto Ricans
turned on a powerful finish late in the final term for a 70-59
win.
</P>
<P>
Puerto Rico strengthened its grip on the gold medal as it
finished the preliminary rounds as the only unbeaten side.
</P>
<P>
But New Zealand gave the favorite a fright, setting the pace
for all but the last 10 minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
New Zealander guard Mark Dickel contributed 10 points and six
assists in a fine first half display and was supported by center
Tony Rampton, who finished the match with 11 points. Forward
Robert Tuilave hit a game-high 13 points and also chipped in with
five rebounds.
</P>
<P>
But Puerto Rico drew away gradually with 10 minutes remaining
and wore down the New Zealanders with a better shot percentage.
</P>
<P>
Center Daniel Santiago finished with 12 points while
fleet-footed guard Eddie Santiago scored 11.
</P>
<P>
Puerto Rican coach Carlos Morales said that he had watched New
Zealand play against Yugoslavia and the United States and did not
underestimate them.
</P>
<P>
"They play very hard and they don't back off from anybody,"
Morales said.
</P>
<P>
In the other match of the first session, Yugoslavia crushed
China 104-51 at the Melbourne Sports and Aquatic Center.
</P>
<P>
Yogoslavia was off to a quick start with guard Dragan Lukovski
running up 17 points for the half, backed up by Vlado Scepanovic
13 and Aleksandar Cubrilo 11.
</P>
<P>
Turkey defeated Korea 84-63 and Argentina beat Egypt
97-58. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
