<HEADLINE> Life Turns Normal in War-Hit Northern Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Schools are resuming operation
and farmers are planting crops with many displaced people having
returned to their homes, "The New Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Peter Odok Wocheng, the resident district commissioner of Gulu
district, told the newspaper that ten primary schools admitted
children and started their operation.
</P>
<P>
And the residents of Lalogi, Odek, Lakwana, Pabbo, Amuru and
Paicho had planted their crops.
</P>
<P>
Authorities in the district mobilized residents, soldiers and
security organs to protect local population, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The relationship between the soldiers and local people is
good, and peace is rapidly returning due to the satisfying work
in the district, Wocheng said.
</P>
<P>
Gulu is one of the four war-hit districts disturbed by the
Lord's Resistance Artmy (LRA) in the north. The LRA rebels had
threatened to kill everyone they meet in the villages in the
north.
</P>
<P>
IRA is a rebel group acting in the north and has bases in
southern Sudan. It is under heavy pressure from Uganda army and
is suffering from lack of food.
</P>
<P>
IRA leader Joseph Kony has sent a message in which he
expressed an intention to surrender to the authorities, an
earlier report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
