<HEADLINE> World Bank Helps Uganda Fighting Lake Weed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank allocated three
billions Ugandan Shillings (about three millions U.S. Dollars) to
fight water hyacinths in Lake Victoria over a five-year period,
"The New Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Thomas J. Mcnabb, the director of Aquatics Inc., told the
paper Tuesday that the money is not yet available because a
control plan is not ready.
</P>
<P>
The money is part of Lake Victoria management program.
</P>
<P>
The total cost for eradicating the weed is yet to be decided
on the control options to be selected by Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The fighting against the weed will be a continuous process due
to the nature of the fast reproducing weed.
</P>
<P>
Scientists estimated that 6,000 hectares of the lake and 80
percent of the shore area of the lake are covered by the weed.
</P>
