<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Bus Blaze Prompts Official Vigilance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's bus companies have
been asked to improve maintenance and prepare for spot-checks
after a fourth major vehicle fire in less than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
A Kowloon Motor Bus (KMB) vehicle caught fire while on road
Sunday. The fire was put out soon by firefighters. There was no
casualty as in the previous three similar incidents.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Transport Department announced tougher tactics
Tuesday including spot-checks of 10 buses a day without prior
notice.
</P>
<P>
Current maintenance adopted by the three major local bus
companies consists only of a visual check.
</P>
<P>
A KMB spokesman said the company's routine inspection is
carried out by the vehicle's captain. If he finds anything
unusual, he reports it to the service engineer.
</P>
<P>
Citybus adopts a similar maintenance system. When a bus
returns to the depot, the mechanics do a visual inspection. The
China Motor Bus services its vehicles on Mondays.
</P>
<P>
But Polytechnic University associate lecturer in mechanical
engineering Lo Kok-keung said that visual checks were insufficient
and probably responsible for the recent fires. Equipment must be
used in the checks, he insisted.
</P>
<P>
Lo described the fires "abnormal" as a diesel engine is really
safe and difficult to catch fire.
</P>
<P>
KMB expects to have re-checked 190 of its Denis 12-meter buses
and 90 MCW 11-meter vehicles by this weekend. Both models caught
fire recently because of dirty engines.
</P>
<P>
A fire in the engine of a Denis 11-meter model Sunday was found
to be caused by a loose bolt on the engine's fuel injection pump
which allowed diesel fuel to leak.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-15 Urges Private Involvement in Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The G-15 Business and Investment
Forum (BIF) meeting concluded in Harare with a call for the
private sector in member countries to be active in the
development of the organization.
</P>
<P>
The delegates underscored the need for the private sector to
take the initiative and become more involved in the activities of
the BIF, at the forum which ended Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They said the private sector must identify potential
investment projects and implement BIF projects to complement the
efforts of governments.
</P>
<P>
G-15, founded in September 1989, is composed of 15 members
from the developing countries in Africa, Asia and Latin America,
aiming at strengthening south-south cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Future BIF meetings, the delegates said, should focus more on
generating concrete business transactions and urged leaders of
chambers of commerce and industry to attend the investment
forums.
</P>
<P>
BIF Chairman Nick Ncube said, "the business sectors need to
affirm their commitment to the BIF and actively participate in
exhibitions, trade fairs and workshops. The private sector
should frequently organize and fund business meetings and appoint
secretariats to facilitate follow-ups."
</P>
<P>
Ncube said, "these participants should make available relevant
information on business interests, costs of labour, product
profiles, pricing and tariff regimes before and during BIF
meetings."
</P>
<P>
Summerizing the meeting, Ncube, who is director of the
Zimbabwe Investment Center, said member countries should set up
national focal points to ensure that the BIF operates
independently but in line with the objectives of the G-15.
</P>
<P>
He said financial packages must be created to increase
economic cooperation and trade among G-15 member states.
</P>
<P>
"In view of this member states may need to investigate the
viability of setting up a G-15 international bank to facilitate
these initiatives," he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting agreed that the removal of trade barriers and
restrictions or delays hampering the movement of labour and
capital in G-15 countries remained a top priority.
</P>
<P>
The delegates resolved that the outcome of the Harare BIF be
presented to heads of state and government at the forthcoming
G-15 summit in Malaysia and facilitate the implementation of
their recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The two-day forum was attended by nine countries -- Algeria,
Argentina, Brazil, Egypt, India, Indonesia, Malaysia, Senegal and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The BIF is a vehicle through which G-15 member countries can
exploit varied trade and investment opportunities brought about
by the globalization of the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Population at 20.56 Million in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's population was
estimated at 20.56 million in 1996, with 19.65 million of them
being Malaysians and the rest foreign nationals, according to
figures released by the Statistics Department today.
</P>
<P>
The figures showed that 16.48 million were in Peninsular
Malaysia, and 2.16 million and 1.92 million in Sabah and Sarawak,
both in East Malaysia, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Among the total population, bumiputras (original inhabitants)
account for 59 percent or 12.13 million, Chinese for 26 percent or
5.34 million and Indians for eight percent or 1.52 million, the
figures showed.
</P>
<P>
Based on age groups, 35.2 percent are 1 to 14 years, 52.3
percent 15 to 49, 6.3 percent 50 to 59, 2.1 per cent 60 to 64 and
4.0 percent 65 years and above.
</P>
<P>
On July 9, National Unity and Social Development Minister
Paduka Zaleha Ismail told a news conference that by June 1997,
Malaysia's population reached 21.66 million with about one third
below 15 years old.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that 56.3 per cent of the population now live
in the urban areas, compared to 51 per cent in 1991, due to a
migration trend to areas of high economic activities.
</P>
<P>
The fertility rate went down from 3.9 to 3.3 during the same
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
