<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Crime Rates Down in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's overall and violent
crime rates in 1996 plummeted 16.1 percent and 13.3 percent
respectively compared with 1995, according to a Fight Crime
Committee (FCC) report which was just released.
</P>
<P>
The overall crime rate stood at 1,253 reported cases per
100,000 people, while the violent crime rate was 241 cases per
100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
There were marked decreases in all robberies (down 29.3
percent), robberies with pistol-like objects (down 48.8 percent),
bank robberies (down 38.1 percent) and theft of motor vehicles
(down 39.9 percent).
</P>
<P>
And the detection rate remained high at 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, juvenile and youth crime continued to be of concern
in the year. There was a drop of 3.6 percent for juvenile
offenders (aged between 7 and 15) and 11.4 percent for young
offenders (aged between 16 and 20) when compared with 1995.
</P>
<P>
The most common offenses committed by juvenile and young
offenders were shoplift, miscellaneous thefts, wounding and
serious assault, and narcotics offenses.
</P>
<P>
Chaired by the administrative secretary, the FCC draws up plans
to reduce crime, coordinate in fighting crime and monitor the
results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
