<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Inflation Down to 17.5 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria recorded an inflation rate
of 17.5 percent in June this year, down from the 19.2 percent for
the previous month, according to the Federal Office of Statistics
(FOS).
</P>
<P>
FOS, the government body for collecting, analyzing and
publishing statistical data, also projected the rates for July
and August at 15.5 and 13.8 percent, respectively, if all things
work according to plan, said a report on local daily, "This Day",
today.
</P>
<P>
The trend indicated that the Nigerian government is likely to
achieve its goal of reducing inflation to 15 percent by the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rate measures the rate of general increase in prices
of goods and services and consequent fall in the purchasing value
of money.
</P>
<P>
The rate has been on the decline in the country since last
year as a result of the tight monetary policy of the government,
from 72.8 percent at the end of 1995 to 28 percent at the end of
last year.
</P>
<P>
The persistent decline in the inflation level and the
brilliant performance of other macroeconomic indicators are a
good testimony to the fact that the economy is on course despite
insinuations to the contrary from some quarters, a government
official was quoted as saying by the paper.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government stock of external reserves shot up
to seven billion U.S. dollars by the end of May from 5.9 billion
in April.
</P>
<P>
"What this means is that government can now finance several
months of export, far more than the four months envisaged in the
1997 budget," a top Finance Ministry official was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The local currency, Naira, has also appreciated against other
currencies, with one U.S. Dollar selling for 83 Naira last week
as against 85 Naira about three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
However, experts noted that despite the declining inflation
rate, all is still not well with the economy. And the cost to
achieve that and increasing foreign reserve remains a question to
many observers.
</P>
<P>
A week ago, the Manufacturing Association of Nigeria (MAN)
raised an alarm on the state of the economy, asking the federal
government to halt the deteriorating state of infrastructure in
the country and save the industries from total collapse.
</P>
<P>
In a memo sent to the head of state, MAN observed that the
poor state of infrastructure has made it difficult for
manufacturing industries to operate especially since they have
had to bear rising cost of production which would not be passed
on to consumers.
</P>
<P>
As a result, most of the warehouses in the country are now
full of unsold stock.
</P>
<P>
"What this means is that inflation is coming down not
necessarily because the economy is performing well, but because
consumers are not buying," said an expert.
</P>
<P>
Experts thus cautioned that bringing inflation down should be
one of the several economic goals of the government.
</P>
<P>
The federal government should also pay attention to the rising
unemployment and population as well as declining consumer
purchasing power and agricultural production, among others, they
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 221 People Killed in South Korean Jet Crash on Guam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 6 (Xinhua) -- At least 221 people were killed in
a pre-dawn crash in Guam of the South Korean Air (KAL) with 231
passengers and 23 crew members on board.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated Boeing 747-300B plane crashed in the forest 4.8
kilometers south of the Agana International Airport, Guam, at
01:55 a.m. local time (15:55 GMT) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Foreign Ministry said that only 30 of the 254
on board had survived, while the KAL announced that the number of
survivors were 33, the Yonhap News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The plane left Seoul at 8:20 p.m. (11:20 GMT) Tuesday and
crashed into a hill after cutting off communication with the
airport's control tower minutes before touching down on Guam.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 217 South Korean passengers were on vacation,
including newly-wed couples off to the Pacific resort island for
their honeymoon. Other passengers include 13 Americans and one
Japanese girl who was luckly enough to survive.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Navy, Air Force and coast guard troops launched rescue
operations immediately after the mishap with helicopters in the
thickly-wooded rain forest.
</P>
<P>
The injured passengers were evacuated to the U.S. Naval
Hospital and Memorial Hospital on the island for treatment. The
number of survivors were worried to decline as several of them
were listed in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
South Korean government officials said that they would look
into all possible causes of the crash, including fuselage defects,
weather condition, guidance system and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
A KAl official said that he had received a report that the Guam
Airport's automatic landing guidance system was malfunctioning,
adding that the exact cause of the crash would be found after
examining the recovered black box.
</P>
<P>
The plane was also suspected to have mechanical failure causing
the fatal crash. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
