<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Oil Production Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's daily crude oil
production hit 2.34 million barrels by the end of June this year,
the Daily Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said this is 6.4 percent up from the 2.2 million
barrels a day in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC)
sources as saying that the increased production mainly came from
two local companies and the two joint ventures NNPC has with
Mobil and Chevron.
</P>
<P>
Mobil's production went up from last year's 450,000 barrels a
day to 530,000 barrels a day, while the production of Chevron
increased from 400,000 to 420,000 barrels a day in the same
period.
</P>
<P>
The NNPC sources, however, argued that the country's output is
still in line with its 1.865-million-barrels-a-day quota from the
Organization of Petroleum Export Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
"The 2.34 million barrels a day level represents the country's
capability and not what its pushing out," a top official was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the application of new technologies
by oil firms has led to more oil finds in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
While Nigeria wants to increase its oil production to three
million barrels a day by the year 2000, Chevron and Mobil have
reportedly taken the targets of 600,000 and 900,000 barrels a
day, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Some industry analysts, however, feared that government budget
cut for the oil sector earlier this year is already having an
adverse effects on the target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
