<HEADLINE> Australian Bourse Marches Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
marched higher today, scoring solid gains across the board ahead
of the release of July employment data tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries closed 19.5 points stronger at 2,727.1,
ignoring Wall Street's 10.91 point fall to 8,187.54 overnight.
</P>
<P>
"The industrials were impressive along with some good
performances by diversified resource stock," a broker said.
</P>
<P>
"The mood was upbeat ahead of tomorrow's employment data
although it's difficult to pin down the drivers."
</P>
<P>
The all resources added 10.2 points to 1,436.8, while the
industrials sector climbed 31.5 points to 4,382.9.
</P>
<P>
Mining giant Rio Tinto gained 32 cents, or 1.56 percent, to
finish at 20.80 Australian dollars. BHP moved up 12 to 17.99
Australian dollars, as did Woodside, ending at 11.37 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the industrials, Coca Cola Amatil surged 35.1 cents, or
2.18 percent, to 16.431 Australian dollars ahead of its interim
net profit, which was announced just minutes after the close of
trade today.
</P>
<P>
The company reported 72.59 million U.S. dollars in after-tax
earnings, taking in contributions from its recently acquired Coca
Cola Bottlers Philippines Inc.
</P>
<P>
Kerry Pack's Publishing and Broadcasting gained 16 to 8.40
Australian dollars and Rupert Murdoch's News Corp closed five
stronger at 6.10 Australian dollars and the company's preferred
shares were up eight to 5.13 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover reached 403.24 million shares worth 776.33
million Australian dollars (574.48 million U.S. dollars), with
rises outpacing falls 534 to 475 and 433 steady.
</P>
<P>
The gold index ended 11.2 points softer at 1,296.7, while gold
bullion was trading 4.35 U.S. dollars lower at 318.55 U.S.
dollars.  
</P>
