<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Defense Chief Resigns for Presidential Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
announced here today he had accepted the resignation of Defense
Secretary Renato de Villa who has decided to run for the
presidency in the 1998 polls.
</P>
<P>
At his weekly press conference, Ramos said he asked de Villa to
stay until 15 September in order to ensure an orderly transition
and search for a replacement.
</P>
<P>
De Villa, who took office in June 1992, will also quit his
other duties such as chairman of the National Disaster
Coordinating Council.
</P>
<P>
Ramos did not mention the reason for the departure of de Villa,
who submitted his letter of resignation on July 20. Neither did de
Villa say why he quit in his resignation letter which was made
public by Ramos today.
</P>
<P>
But it is widely believed that de Villa quit because of
mounting pressure from the opposition camp and in order to prepare
for his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
Proclaimed presidential aspirants from the opposition camp
accused de Villa of taking advantage of his present position to
promote his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
De Villa earlier publicly proclaimed his bid to run for the
presidency in the May 1998 polls and joined the ruling Lakas-NUCD
(National Union of Christian Democrats) party in late June to
compete for the party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party led by Ramos is expected to hold a national
convention to choose its presidential bet in November.
</P>
<P>
With the resignation of de Villa, the struggle among the ruling
party for the anointment of Ramos as the party's standard bearer
in next year's presidential polls will get more bitter, political
observers said.
</P>
<P>
Other contenders for Ramos' backing include his economic
adviser Emilio Osmena, Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo and his
younger sister Senator Leticia Ramos-Shahani. De Ocampo, who is
not a Lakas member, said he will join the party soon.
</P>
<P>
Opposition presidential contenders include Vice President
Joseph Estrada and Senate President Maceda. Estrada had already
resigned from his only cabinet post, chairman of the Presidential
Anti-Crime Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
