<HEADLINE> All Nepalese to Have Health Services by 2000: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has been
working to fulfill its commitment to provide health services to
every Nepalese by the year 2000, Health Minister Radha Krishna
Mainali said.
</P>
<P>
Programs for providing maternity child services, training
14,000 midwives, distributing health materials, providing health
education for 43,000 women volunteers and launching a vaccination
campaign are being carried out throughout the country, today's
Nepali newspapers quoted the Mainali as telling parliament
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the maternity and child mortality rate has
declined, Mainali said the safe motherhood program being launched
in 10 districts will be strengthened and extended to other
districts.
</P>
<P>
He said the establishment of an emergency hospital in Chitwan
district of southern Nepal is being discussed.
</P>
<P>
The targets of the health sector cannot be achieved without the
overall development of safe drinking water, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is determined to enforce and follow up
such programs.
</P>
<P>
The minister also promised that the capacity of district
hospitals will be increased during the Ninth Five Year Plan
(1997-2002) period and more doctors will be provided.
</P>
<P>
Most hospitals in Nepal run far short of doctors.  
</P>
