<HEADLINE> China, New Zealand Reach Agreement on WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- China and New Zealand reached an
agreement on the conclusion of the bilateral market access talks
related to China's access to the World Trade Organization (WTO)
here today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was initialled by Long Yongtu, chief negotiator
of the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
(MOFTEC), and Alastair Bisley, deputy secretary of the New Zealand
Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade.
</P>
<P>
Minister of MOFTEC Wu Yi and New Zealand Minister of
International Trade Lockwood Smith attended the initialling
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
China and New Zealand have recently held friendly and frank
negotiations on China's access to WTO.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand side expressed gratitude to China for its great
efforts in resolving the issue of market access for wool and other
products, efforts made under the direct supervision of Chinese
leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side appreciated New Zealand's flexible and
realistic attitude shown during the talks.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side said that New Zealand is the first country to
start market access talks with China under the framework of the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). It has actively
push ahead China's access to a multilateral trade system.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side believes that fact that this time New Zealand
took the lead to reach an agreement with China on this matter will
add a strong impetus to the process of multilateral talks on
China's access to WTO. It will also promote the expansion of
economic and trade relations between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
