<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State Enterprise Reforms (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has made some progress in its reform and opening-up
efforts, since the 14th National Congress of the Communist Party
of China (CPC) in October 1992. For this fall's 15th National
Congress, Xinhua is providing an outline of the third generation
of leaders of the CPC Central Committee, headed by Jiang Zemin,
and how it has followed Deng Xiaoping's theory of building
socialism with Chinese characteristics. This is the third part of
the series.
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- China has done some experiments
in reforming its state-owned enterprises since the 14th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China in 1992 developed the
strategy for establishing a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
In the intervening years, particularly the past five, a way has
been found for some sluggish state enterprises to restructure
themselves.
</P>
<P>
The Company Law of 1993 pointed the way for organizing
companies from state-owned enterprises, a novel reform method.
</P>
<P>
After that, state enterprises were restructured by establishing
a modern enterprise system to meet the needs of a socialist market
economy, by clarifying property rights and responsibilities, and
by separating the functions of the government from those of
enterprises, and with more scientific management.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the state started the project in 100 large and
medium-sized enterprises, and later, more than 2,000 state
enterprises experimented with the modern enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
By now, most enterprises have been re-organized into companies
and nearly half have issued shares. More than half of the general
managers of the newly re-organized companies are appointed by
board of directors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State Enterprise Reforms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the experimental period, state assets tended to grow and
the companies had better returns.
</P>
<P>
The reforms also provided valuable experience and laid a solid
foundation for the modern enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
Priority is given to a mechanism in which the most competitive
companies survive, so outmoded industrial methods have to be
improved and enterprises with heavy losses are allowed to declare
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the central government selected 18 cities to support
the reform measures and improving enterprises' use of
capital. This is meant to change operations, provide new funds,
relieve them of their debt and social burdens, find jobs for
redundant employees, establish a social security system, and help
them become more competitive.
</P>
<P>
So far, 111 cities, almost all of them major industrial cities,
have adopted the pilot measures. The state set aside 20 billion
yuan (2.4 billion US dollars) in bank funds last year, and will
set aside 30 billion yuan this year, for mergers and bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
The state has also put more funds into help with some
technological improvements to help competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The pilot work has given officials, employees, and the general
public a better understanding of mergers and bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, China's highest administrative body, has
also backed 57 large enterprise groups, many of which have merged,
purchased, combined with or taken into trusteeship a large number
of other enterprises that were having difficulties in the last few
years.
</P>
<P>
The enterprise groups have seen assets grow and sales increase,
and they now play a greater role in their own industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
