<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State Enterprise Reforms (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The central government has decided that this year there will be
120 experimental enterprise groups with certain decision-making
powers.
</P>
<P>
Some of better qualified ones can take the lead in setting up
finance companies and raising funds abroad, and in stocks and bond
issues.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, local governments have made some of the more
than 240,000 small state-owned businesses enter the market by
restructuring, combining, leasing, or selling them.
</P>
<P>
In the process of reforming state enterprises, the State
Council has been urging those in charge to adopt better management
methods as required by the market economy.
</P>
<P>
The Handan Iron and Steel Company in north China's Hebei
Province has set a good example for others in this with its good
management.
</P>
<P>
In using the company's experience in 1994, state enterprises in
the metallurgy sector had better profits than other sectors in
spite of a market slump and financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The central government is determined to do a thorough study
this year on the leadership of state enterprises, and those that
don't meet the reform and economic development needs will be
reorganized.
</P>
<P>
Economists believe that state-owned enterprises will be able to
have some success and be revitalized in the end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
