<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inland City Fosters Economic Pillars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Xi'an, home of terra-cotta
warriors, vows to build four major industries to help with local
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
This capital city of northwest China's Shaanxi province has
designated electronics and information, transportation, electric
equipment and tourism as four economic pillars for the local
economy.
</P>
<P>
All four areas have a solid foundation for future development.
</P>
<P>
New electronic products are the focus of local developers.
</P>
<P>
The local Datang Telecom Corp. is now one of China's major
digital switchboard producers with a capacity of two million lines.
</P>
<P>
Also, companies in the city have formed a computer production
capacity of 60,000 units a year.
</P>
<P>
Other products on the development list are microwave and
satellite equipment, as well as Chinese-based software products.
</P>
<P>
In the field of transport, the city plans to focus on the
manufacture of aircraft, train wagons, and automobiles.
</P>
<P>
Yun-7 plane, developed by Xi'an Aircraft Manufacture
Corporation, is now China's backbone local-made model flying on
domestic routes.
</P>
<P>
The Xi'an Rail Vehicle Factory holds a major share of the local
rail vehicle market.
</P>
<P>
Xifei-Volvo deluxe buses produced by a Sino-Volvo joint venture
can rival with foreign models in the marketplace. Other auto
products, including cars, heavy-duty trucks and mining vehicles
made by local makers were also recognized by the users.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an is now also one of China's major electric equipment
producers. Xidian Corp., the largest among all local companies,
last year earned 55.94 million US dollars in foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
As a famous cultural and historic site in China, the city
accomodated some 480,000 overseas visitors and 9.6 million
domestic travelers last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
