<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economist on Reform of State-Owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A prominent Chinese economist
says that a socialist market economy's goal is to combine social
equality with market efficiency, and the state-owned enterprise
reforms must work toward this goal.
</P>
<P>
Dong Fureng, vice-chairman of the Financial Committee of the
National People's Congress, in an article carried in Beijing's
Economic Reference Daily, said that China has replaced its planned
economy with the socialist market economy because it is more
efficient.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the market economy has its weakpoints or
shortcomings, he said, one of which is its unfair distribution
owing to market competition leading to shifts in wealth and unfair
distribution of it.
</P>
<P>
Socialism's fundamental demand is social fairness. Therefore,
the goal of China's current economic reforms conforms to the
country's socio-economic goals.
</P>
<P>
To do this, the state-owned enterprises should do what the
non-state firms can't do by providing the government with the
means to interfere in and regulate the market. A certain number of
state-owned or state-controled commercial banks, non-bank
financial institutions and warehousing enterprises are necessary.
</P>
<P>
The state has to invest in non-profitable public facilities,
infrastructure, and hi-tech industries that the non-public sector
is unwilling or unable to get involved in because of the
difficulty in making a profit and the risks.
</P>
<P>
The State-owned enterprises should be set up where a state
monopoly is needed, like the weaponry industry or currency
printing sector. If state enterprises are maintained in these
sectors, state-owned assets of other industries that do not need
to be maintained could be transferred for development purposes.
</P>
<P>
Assets of state firms could be transferred to the non-state
sector and profits from their sale could be used to pay off bank
debts to relieve banks of the burden or for resettlement of the
surplus labor force, and bankruptcies of certain companies could
prevent further losses. Funds from the transfer could be used for
pensions or finding jobs for laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
After the transfer, the number of state-owned firms needed
would be substantially reduced and the state exchequer and banks
could also use the funds to help the remaining state companies in
technological improvements or development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
