<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Port City Becomes New Tourist Attraction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIANYUNGANG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Lianyungang, a summer resort
on the border between east China's Jiangsu and Shandong provinces,
has become a popular tourist destination in recent years.
</P>
<P>
It played host to 900,000 domestic and foreign visitors in
1996, doubling the previous year's figure.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, the number of tourists
surpassed one million and revenue gained from the tourist industry
totalled 700 million yuan, exceeding the annual income of last
year.
</P>
<P>
A local tourism official cited fresh air, fine scenery and low
prices as the major attractions for visitors.
</P>
<P>
Another key factor was the improvement of infrastructures and
development of new tourist spots in recent years, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Haizhouwan Villa, opened in early July, has a 11-km-long
high-quality beach, built with an investment of 60 million yuan,
half of which were provided by local farmers.
</P>
<P>
The operation of a new shipping route between Shanghai and
Lianyungang made travel to this summer resort more convenient.
</P>
</TEXT>
