<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Borrow From IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government is expected
to borrow at least 10 billion U.S. dollars to support its foreign
exchange reserves, Thai Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The funds will be used to support and prevent the country's
current 32.4 billion dollars of foreign exchange reserves from
sliding down below the level of 25 billion dollars, the minister
was quoted as saying by local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The Thai cabinet Tuesday approved a comprehensive fiscal and
monetary reform plan to pave the way for borrowing from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF). But it did not mention in a
statement the amount it hopes to borrow.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is negotiating with the IMF on details of the
borrowing, Thanong said.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that Thailand is also considering borrowing
more from other countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
