<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China's Yantai Port Starts Third-Phase Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Workers have recently started
third-phase construction of the Yantai Port in east China's
Shandong Province after about five years' preparation.
</P>
<P>
According to port officials, they plan to build seven
deep-water berths of 10,000 dwt (dead weight tonnages), including
two berths for containers, and to build other supporting
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The construction project will be completed in seven years at an
estimate cost of 2.2 billion yuan. Financing will be met by loans
provided by the Asian Development Bank, the State Development Bank
of China, and with funds raised by the Yantai Port Administration.
</P>
<P>
Another motor vehicle ferry wharf, with an annual passing
capacity of 380,000 motor vehicles and 950,000 tons of cargo, has
been built in preparation for the formal start of the third-phase
construction. It has survived test and has been put into use.
</P>
<P>
Situated in the northern side of the Shandong Peninsula and
looking to the Liaodong Peninsula beyond the sea, Yantai is a
major marine shipping hub and an important open port on the east
China coast.
</P>
<P>
Yantai Port will have 38 berths on completion of the
first-period construction of the third stage, including 19
deep-water berths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
