<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tea Production Down in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's tea production fell by
around 28 percent in the first six months of 1997 compared with
the same period last year due to bad weather, the East African
Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
Tea yield totaled 96.73 million kilograms in Kenya between
January and June, a decrease of 37.6 million kilograms or 27.99
percent compared with the same period in 1996, said a statement
from the leading brokerage company Africa Tea Brokers Ltd. (ATB).
</P>
<P>
The crop figure for June 1997 was 16.264 million kilograms, a
fall of 1.634 million kilograms or 9.13 percent over the same
month last year, according to the statement issued on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Most tea-growing areas in the country remained cold and wet
last month, resulting in the inhibition of tea growth and the
reduction of plucking rounds, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"Currently, with slightly warmer temperatures, leaf intake
will show a gradual improvement" in most tea-yielding areas, the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
Kenya was the world's leading exporter of black tea last year
with a record production of 257 million kilograms. Tea is second
behind tourism as the main hard currency earner of the eastern
African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
