<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Schools in S. Africa in Poor Conditions: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- South African Education
Minister Sibusiso Bengu has confirmed that most schools in the
country are either in bad conditions, or in need of facilities.
</P>
<P>
Bengu on Tuesday quoted a recent comprehensive register of
education institutions as saying that nearly a quarter of the
country's schools had no water within walking distance, less than
half of the schools had electricity, and many schools experienced
a shortage of toilets.
</P>
<P>
According to the register, school buildings in many provinces
are in bad conditions. The most serious problems were in Northern
Province, where 41 percent of school buildings are in a weak or
very weak state.
</P>
<P>
Facilities such as laboratories and workshops at secondary
schools are virtually non-existent. Most schools in the former
"Black Homeland" are the worst off.
</P>
<P>
"These shocking findings are an indictment of all who by
commission or ommission allowed this injustice to occur in this
country.
</P>
<P>
"It is the worst form of human degradation to condemn children
to an educational enviroment without toilets, libraries,
laboratories, water, classrooms," Bangu said, stressing this had
to be changed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
