<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourists Flock To South China Beaches For Holidays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Chen Jianyun, a farmer in the
southern part of China, has joined some 20,000 other
holiday-makers flocking to the beaches of Beihai City these days.
</P>
<P>
"A dozen friends and I plan to stay in Beihai for a week, and
we'll spend most of the time swimming in the sea," the 21-year-old
woman from Yulin in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, said.
</P>
<P>
Because she and her family earn about 40,000 yuan (4,800 US
dollars) yearly from farming and growing litchis, she can well
afford the trip, she said.
</P>
<P>
The Beihai Yintan (Silver Beach) Holiday Resort on the Beibu
Gulf has become a popular spot for holiday-makers. Every day, as
many as 30,000 people can be seen lying under colorful parasols or
swimming in the blue waters of the 12 beaches.
</P>
<P>
"The beaches, unusual forests, and fresh air are what drew us
to Beihai," Miss Chen said. These are also what has changed Beihai
from a small backwater town to a national holiday resort, one that
has had 10 million tourists since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The tourism boom has brought with it luxury hotels, spas,
parks, swimming pools, and bowling alleys. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
