<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Use High-Tech in Dunhuang Grotto Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, August 6 (Xinhua) -- China is to introduce laser
technology, infrared photography and some other high-tech methods
in the protection of the Dunhuang Grottoes.
</P>
<P>
In cooperation with scientific research institutions both at
home and abroad, the Dunhuang Research Institute will launch
projects in sand-proof, computer inputing of frescoes in Dunhuang
caves dating from 366 A.D., resuming the original colors of the
frescoes and biological protection research.
</P>
<P>
Li Shi, deputy director of an institute attached to the
Dunhuang Research Institute, said some of the projects are being
prepared.
</P>
<P>
He said that more than 3,000 meters of a sand-proof shield was
built atop the Dunhuang Grottoes which reduced over 70 percent of
the sandfalls in front of the Dunhuang caves.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, as shifting sand on the top of the caves has
became a new problem, Chinese and US researchers are to improve
the sand-proof system for the grottoes.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists also decided to use infrared photographic
techniques to resume the original looks of the mural, as the
original color on many parts of the mural has faded and the mural
became darkened.
</P>
<P>
Li said as biological molds have seriously eroded the mural,
his institute is to seek a biological protection method for saving
the mural.
</P>
<P>
He added that for permanent protection of the Dunhuang mural,
several research institutions have combined efforts to input the
Dunhuang frescoes into computers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Helps Manila Clean Up Pasig River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
said today that it has granted a total of 800,000 U.S. dollars in
technical assistance to help clean up the Pasig River, the main
waterway flowing through Metro Manila.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based bank said the grant would assist a government
plan for the rehabilitation of the river which has been heavily
polluted by industrial, municipal and household wastes.
</P>
<P>
According to the ADB, the current level of pollution in the
river is 45 percent industrial waste, 45 percent municipal waste
water and 10 percent domestic solid waste.
</P>
<P>
The grant would also help Manila improve the quality of Pasig
River water so that it would be able to sustain aquatic life and
be used for water sports like boating by the year 2008, the ADB
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
