<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Entrepreneurs Invest in State Firms In North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- More than 50 farmers who have
become entrepreneurs have assumed the post of directors or general
managers at small money-losing factories in north China's Shanxi
Province through public bidding.
</P>
<P>
They have produced more than 200 million yuan worth of goods
and saved 40 small and unprofitable state enterprises in the
process. The move has also allowed 2,400 laid-off workers to
return to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
One chemical works in Shouyang County, which used to be the
largest state firm in the county had lost 19 million yuan as
the result of poor management and lack of operating capital.
</P>
<P>
Yue Quansheng, a farmer turned entrepreneur, was invited to be
director of the chemical works, and in three years succeeded in
getting pre-tax profits of 10 million yuan by introducing
competitive methods and improving technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
