<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyans Urged Avoiding Dependency on Foreign Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
has urged Kenyans not to panic over the suspension of aid to
Kenya by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and work hard to
avoid dependency on foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
Considering the difficult economic situation affecting the
world in general, Kenyans should not expect much in terms of
external assistance, he said in Nyeri District, southern Kenya,
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He also called for proper management of Kenya's resources for
sustainable economic development, urging all Kenyans to be united
and work together for self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he played down the effect of the IMF aid cut,
saying the suspended 215-million-U.S.-Dollar loan is "very small
compared with the government's annual expenditure of 161 billion
Shillings (2.93 billion Dollars) as recorded last year."
</P>
<P>
The deficit would be compensated by revenue generated from
agriculture and other sectors and the whole economy would not be
threatened, he said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF announced Thursday it held back a three-year Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF) because of the alleged
failure of the Kenyan government "to show its commitment to
fighting corruption," and this aroused strong reactions in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors pulled out of the Nairobi Stock Exchange in
droves on Friday by selling 250 million Shillings (4.1 million
Dollars) of the fourth issue of the Central Bank of Kenya
floating-rate treasury bond.
</P>
<P>
They only sold 13.35 million Shillings (243,000 Dollars)
during the whole of the previous week, traders said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
