<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, August 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A South Korean Air jet with 254 on board crashed
and burned early Wednesday when it was trying to land at Guam's
A.B. Won Pat International Airport. At least 35 people aboard the
Boeing 747 survived the crash that occurred five kilometers from
the airport at about 1:50 a.m. local time (15:50 GMT Tuesday),
said U.S. Navy officials.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Two oxygen generators on board the Mir space station
have failed, a spokesman for the Russian ground control center
said on Tuesday. He said the craft's oxygen-producing electrolysis
equipment broke down a few days ago, but he described the incident
as routine.
</P>
<P>
SARAJEVO -- Croatian President Franjo Tudjman Tuesday was sworn
in for the second five-year term in office. Addressing the
swearing-in ceremony, he said that Croatia attaches special
importance to cooperation with the United States and the European
Union and pays special attention to the development of friendly
relations with Central European countries as well as with China,
Russia and Islamic countries.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States Tuesday called Israel's
suspension of its reimbursement of taxes owed to the Palestinian
Authority "counterproductive" to the peace process in the Middle
East. State Department spokesman James Foley called on Israel to
resume the reimbursement in accordance with its agreements with
the Palestinians to transfer to the Palestinian Authority of
nearly 500 million U.S. dollars that it collects each year from
Palestinians who work or buy goods in Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Minister: Use Domestic Resources for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Developing economies should make
full use of domestic resources to achieve growth and development,
South African Minister of Trade and Industry Alec Erwin said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing more than 600 delegates to the 54th Zimbabwean
Commerce Farmers' (CFU) congress, Erwin said the natural wealth
in the Southern African region was its greatest asset which, if
exploited in a sustainable manner, would lead to the development
of the region's economies.
</P>
<P>
He urged countries in the region to trade among themselves and
not to favor trade with industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same function, CFU President Nick Swanepoel
told delegates that increasing financial returns from agriculture
were necessary for Zimbabwe's national growth and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
These returns were essential if farmers were to maintain
services, downstream business activities and employment growth,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to reconsider its position and
priorities with respect to the allocation of funds to
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Zimbabwe's competitiveness as an agricultural
exporter had declined more than any of the 12 Southern African
Development Community (SADC) member countries due to the decline
of domestic support for the sector by the government and
increased levels of direct taxation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
