<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> KAL Jet Might Have Mechanical Failure Before Crashing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The ill-fated Korean Air (KAL)
plane, which crashed in Guam early this morning, dropped to the
ground in two fiery pieces, raising speculation that the plane had
some mechanical problems before reaching the ground, a Foreign
Ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
"Staff of the South Korean Consulate General in Agana, Guam,
saw the aircraft falling from the sky in two blazing pieces," said
Deputy Foreign Minister Hong Jung-pyo.
</P>
<P>
The exact cause of the crash, however, will be revealed only
after the air transportation authorities of South Korea and the
U.S. finish examining records of the flight and the scene, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
The blackbox, which will provide the information about the
crash, was recovered and is being sent to Washington D.C., the
Central Accident Countermeasure Headquarters here said.
</P>
<P>
Various stories on the cause of the crash were reported so far,
mostly focusing on the weather conditions and possible mechanical
failures.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the U.S. Federal Aviation Agency said the glide
slope, a landing system at the airport, was out of order.
</P>
<P>
Some survivors are reporting that they heard strange noise in
the flight right after its departure at Seoul's Kimpo Airport.
</P>
<P>
The last message from the plane was "something wrong", Lee
Tae-won, vice president of KAL said.
</P>
<P>
On contrary, some experts suspect heavy rains caused the crash.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses described a "tropical downpour" at the time of the
accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
