<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 07:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Peace Movement Attacks Government's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Israel's organization Peace
Now charged the government with being intent on destroying the
peace process by planning more settlements, The Jerusalem Post
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Opposition lawmaker Ran Cohen, a Peace Now member, was quoted
as saying that the government is planning to build 42,000 new
housing units in different stages in settlements in the Binyamin
region in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said the government is secretly carrying out plans for
mass building in the settlements without the public's
knowledge. He added that the Peace Now's statistics are based on
information gathered from government sources, visiting sites in
the area and from the settlers.
</P>
<P>
"Such construction will cause a total explosion of the peace
process and the end of dialogue with the Palestinians and the
Arab world," Cohen warned at a news conference held Tuesday in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Mossi Raz, Director of Peace Now, stressed that the majority
of the settlements mentioned are deep in the West Bank, many of
them small and isolated.
</P>
<P>
In response, the Israeli Defense Ministry issued a statement
rejecting the Peace Now's charges. It denied there are any new
settlements being constructed in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israel's expansion of settlements is the stumbling obstacle
in advancing the Israeli-Palestinian peace process which has been
frozen since March when Israel began building the Har Homa
settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority has been demanding a halt
to the settlement expansion before resuming and advancing the
peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Offers Jobs, Education to Solve Drug Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The government of Mandaluyong in
Metro Manila is providing employment, livelihood activities and
education to help curb the serious drug problem in the city.
</P>
<P>
Mandaluyong Councilor Benjamin Abalos launched the program for
drug abusers and potential victims under the supervision of the
city government, the Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Abalos was quoted as saying the solution to the drug problem is
to offer jobs and education to the victims of illicit drugs as
research showed that unemployment contributes most to the problem.
</P>
<P>
Abalos' findings jibed with the recent studies of the Dangerous
Drugs Board which show that drug addiction often results from lack
of jobs and educational opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, the city government would provide education
opportunities through a special scholarship to young people who
were driven to drugs.
</P>
<P>
"If we can address these issues effectively, we can put a stop
to the vice (illegal drugs) and provide people with better
alternatives in life," Abalos said.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that 1.7 million Filipinos are drug addicts and
80 percent of them are aged between 25 and 29.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
