<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gigantic Thunder Strikes Jiuzhi in Qinghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A gigantic thunder struck Jiuzhi
County in northwest China's Qinghai Province days ago and more
than 100 people reported an experience of an electric shock.
</P>
<P>
An investigation made county government officials showed that
the thunder burned nine television sets, 21 telephone sets and a
number of other domestic electric appliances.
</P>
<P>
Residents in the county seat, which is 3,200 meters above sea
level on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, recalled that when the thunder
landed, houses shaked and people felt like experiencing an
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
An expert with the Qinghai Provincial Meterological Bureau said
Jiuzhi County is often struck by heavy thunders.
</P>
<P>
He said the average annual precipitation is about 800 mm. The
high elevation narrows the distance between water-bearing clouds
and the ground, which provides fine conditions for thunders.
</P>
<P>
He said the lastest thunder strike in Jiuzhi County was a
direct hit on buildings which could cause serious damage.
</P>
<P>
As thunders have brought about casualties of people and cattle
in the province each year, the province has established thunder
monitoring stations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China Fighting Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province is fighting a battle against a severe drought that has
affected more than 1.3 million ha of farmland
</P>
<P>
Most parts of the province have had less than ten mm
of precipitation this summer and temperatures have been two to
five degrees Celsius higher than usual. This has resulted in
withered crops on 600,000 ha of farmland.
</P>
<P>
In the western part of the province, one of the important grain
production bases, farmers are carrying water by every possible
means. In the northern part of the province, people have been
organized to dig wells.
</P>
<P>
Irrigation projects are an important part of the campaign, and
the provincial irrigation department has sent six groups to rural
areas to help farmers fight the drought.
</P>
<P>
Nanchengzhi reservoir has provided farmland on the lower
reaches of the Liaohe River with 20 million cubic meters of water
and more than 100 ponds have helped provide relief from the
drought. And large state-owned enterprises have come up with more
than 10,000 buckets to support the struggle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Plane Crashes on Guam, Some 200 Killed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A South Korean Air jet with
254 on board crashed and burned early Wednesday when it was trying
to land at Guam's A.B. Won Pat International Airport.
</P>
<P>
At least 35 people aboard the Boeing 747 survived the crash
that occurred five kilometers from the airport at about 1:50
a.m. local time (15:50 GMT Tuesday), said U.S. Navy officials.
</P>
<P>
But, the airline's officials put the number of survivors at 50.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which was on a routine flight between the South
Korean capital of Seoul and Guam, was carrying 231 passengers and
23 crew members, mostly Korean tourists, when it went down in the
hills during an attempted landing.
</P>
<P>
Some witnesses said they saw flames or heard an explosion
before the plane went down.
</P>
<P>
As the plane crashed, it hit an oil pipeline that runs through
the rugged jungle area, causing the line to rupture and spill
about 1,000 gallons of aviation fuel. But the fuel did not catch
fire as the break came away from the crash site, U.S. Navy
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. National Transportation Safety Board had sent an
18-member team from Washington to investigate the accident. An
investigation member said the voice and flight-data recorders had
been recovered from the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
Officials on Guam had confirmed that the airport landing system
known as the glide slope, which leads planes to the runway, had
not been in service at the airport since last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
