<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Booming in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The private sector in Shanghai,
China's largest industrial center, has grown to contribute five
percent to local revenues, and is expected to play an increasingly
more important role in economic development.
</P>
<P>
More than 8,000 new private businesses have been launched
during the first half of this year in Shanghai, making the total
number to 62,000, involving 657,000 employees, China Business
Times reported.
</P>
<P>
The average registered capital for each business is nearly
600,000 yuan, 20 percent more than the national average.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Municipal Government gave more autonomy to its
districts and counties in managing enterprises. As a result, those
districts and counties have developed 72 industrial parks for
private firms. Now, 75 percent of the city's private sector have
settled in the parks.
</P>
<P>
In some districts and counties, private enterprises contribute
30 percent to local revenues.
</P>
<P>
The sector has employed a tenth of the city's workers,
including more than 100,000 laid-offs and some 300,000 rural
laborers, the newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
