<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hiroshima Marks 52nd Anniversary of A-Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Hiroshima today marked the 52nd
anniversary of the atomic bombing of the city by calling for the
elimination of nuclear weapons and praying for those who died from
the blast, Kyodo News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
Some 45,000 people, including victims of the attack and those
who lost relatives, gathered at Peace Memorial Park, located near
the point of the bomb explosion.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, along with
dignitaries from many countries, also attended the ceremony and
offered flowers at a cenotaph for bomb victims at the Peace
Memorial Ceremony.
</P>
<P>
At 8:15 a.m., the exact time of the blast, participants at the
ceremony offered one minute of silent prayer.
</P>
<P>
Hiroshima Mayor Takashi Hiraoka delivered a peace declaration
and appealed to the world for the elimination of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
"We in Hiroshima are outraged that nuclear weapons have yet to
be abolished and banished from the face of the earth," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also called for a swift ratification of the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) and strongly criticized a subcritical
nuclear test conducted by the United States in early July.
</P>
<P>
After 1,500 doves symbolizing peace were released, Hashimoto
delivered a speech and called a nuclear-free world "the fervent
wish" of his country which is "the only country to suffer an
atomic bombing in human history."
</P>
<P>
The atomic bomb was dropped on Hiroshima on August 6, 1945, by
the U.S. B-29 bomber "Enola Gay." The bomb destroyed the city and
was responsible for the deaths of an estimated 140,000 people by
the end of 1945. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
