<HEADLINE> North China Province Using Foreign Funds For Key Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Shanxi Province in north China,
which is using overseas capital for key projects, recently was
approved by the World Bank for a 400-million-yuan water diversion
project in Pianguan County.
</P>
<P>
The loan is a sixth of the bank's total loans for China this
year. It will be used for the first phase of a warter-diversion
project, from the Yellow River to Taiyuan city, the provincial
capital.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi can apply for bank loans for the second phase as soon as
the first phase construction is underway, said Mr. Daniel
Gunaratnam, a bank official who has been overseeing the water
diversion project.
</P>
<P>
Construction work on the Yangcheng Power Plant, China's first
inter-provincial thermal power plant, has begun. It is expected to
transmit all its electricity over a 755-km high-voltage wire to east
China's Jiangsu Province by 1999.
</P>
<P>
The plant has a 2.1 million kw annual capacity and will cost
13.2 billion yuan, nearly 900 million US dollars of which comes
from overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi and Hong Kong have established two highway investment
companies, with 60 million US dollars in registered funds. And
five banks from Hong Kong and Macao provided 24 million US dollars
in highway loans earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to expand co-operation with overseas
investors to other sectors, relying on the build-operate-transfer
(BOT) method. 
</P>
</TEXT>
