<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Expanding Economic Cooperation with Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, Aug 6 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province will
accelerate economic cooperation with Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Wang Chuntao, director of the provincial Commission of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation, says that he is confident about
economic cooperation prospects between Shandong and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Shandong is one of China's fastest developing provinces
economically, and has increasingly mature, large markets with many
resources, which Hong Kong lacks, Wang said. At the same time,
Shandong needs Hong Kong's capital and advanced industrial
technology. Hong Kong has now become Shandong's biggest investor
and one of its most important trading partners.
</P>
<P>
From 1978 to 1996, the total volume of trade between Shandong
and Hong Kong reached 13 billion dollars, accounting for 14
percent of the total trade volume of the province.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, the Provincial Government had approved
processing trade zones in the cities of Liaocheng and Heze in an
effort to attract more investment. And in order to strengthen
Shandong-Hong Kong economic and trade relations, Shandong will
open markets further in Australia and the South Pacific and
further develop transit trade with Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Shandong will also become an increasingly large market for Hong
Kong products, especially consumer goods, and Hong Kong will need
more raw materials and semi-finished products from Shandong.
</P>
<P>
During the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000), Shandong
plans to get 18 billion U.S. dollars worth of direct foreign
investment, something that will be a strong inducement for Hong
Kong investment, which is expanding northward from China's
southeast coastal areas, especially after Hong Kong's return.
</P>
<P>
Since 1981, there have been 9,300 Shandong-Hong Kong ventures
and solely Hong Kong-backed enterprises in Shandong, accounting for
43 percent of the province's foreign-funded enterprises.
Contractual investment from Hong Kong amounted to 11.4 billion
dollars and actually utilized capital, more than 5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, more than 3,400 of the Hong
Kong-backed firms have been begun operation in Shandong,
accounting for 42 percent of the foreign-funded enterprises
operating there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
