<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Parties' "Soft Money" Multiply, Says Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The two major political
parties in the United States, the Republican and Democratic
parties, have multiplied the "soft money" they raised over recent
years, a report released today by an advocacy group said.
</P>
<P>
The two parties received a total of 34 million dollars in the
first half of 1997, which is more than double the 13 million
dollars they raised in the six months following the last
presidential election, said Common Cause, a nonprofit group
advocating for tighter controls on campaign money.
</P>
<P>
Republican committees raised 23 million dollars, while the
Democrats got 11 million during the first six months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Together, the Democrats and Republicans raised 262 million
dollars in soft money in the two years leading up to the 1996
election, which triples the amount raised just four years earlier,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Soft money is supposed to be spent on party-building activities
such as get-out-the-vote drives, and not on promoting individual
candidates.
</P>
<P>
But both parties have got more creative in using soft money and
poured millions into advertisements aimed at influencing last
year's presidential election, the report pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"Congress must act...to end the discredited soft money system
that is overwhelming elections and poisoning our political
system," Common Cause President Ann McBride has said.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton and some lawmakers have also called for
a ban on soft money and the Federal Election Commission (FEC) is
studying the matter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Output of Hops to Take Drastic Decline: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The production of hops in the Czech
Republic will drop 25 percent to 8,000 tons this year, an official
of the hops growers' association said.
</P>
<P>
The recent devastating flood and shortage of capital are being
blamed for the reduction.
</P>
<P>
The flood, the biggest in recent years, damaged large stretches
of fields used for growing hops, while the actual acreage used for
growing hops dropped 17 percent for lack of money.
</P>
<P>
Hops, known as "green gold" in the Czech Republic, is essential
for beer production and is the country's biggest foreign exchange
earner. The Czech Republic exports two thirds of its hops.
</P>
<P>
Czech hops are reputed to be the best in the world and are
often used in international markets as the standard against which
hops from other countries are tested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Adopts Plan to Win IMF Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet Tuesday adopted
a comprehensive fiscal and monetary reform plan to streamline the
country's finance sector in an apparent bid to meet conditions to
win rescue aid from the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The most radical measure under the plan is the government's
decision to suspend 42 finance firms, including subsidiaries of
Thailand's leading commercial banks, such as Bangkok Bank, Thai
Farmers Bank and Siam Commercial Bank.
</P>
<P>
In announcing the suspension, the Thai Finance Ministry said in
a statement that the measure is aimed at separating those
unhealthy finance institutions from healthy ones in a bid to raise
confidence of creditors in the sector.
</P>
<P>
The announcement put the total number of suspended finance
firms at 58, as the government had earlier this year already
suspended operations of 16 finance firms which were short of
funds.
</P>
<P>
The announcement sent a fresh shock wave through the local
finance and banking markets.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Stock Exchange of Thailand suspended trading in
the finance and banking sector and people flocked to some of the
finance firms to withdraw their funds.
</P>
<P>
However, the government said it will protect depositors and
creditors of the suspended firms, which have been ordered to
present rehabilitation plans within 60 days before they can
restore operations.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the government provides guidelines and
macroeconomic action plans and measures to tackle the country's
current economic problems.
</P>
<P>
"The economic and fiscal and monetary problem that urgently
needs to be resolved is to restore confidence in the stability of
the fiscal and monetary system," the government said in a lengthy
press release available today.
</P>
<P>
Thailand will make efforts to maintain its foreign exchange
reserves at a level not less than 25 billion U.S. dollars, or
sufficient to support 3.5 months' imports and resolve the crisis
affecting the financial system.
</P>
<P>
As part of its macroeconomic action plans and measures, the
Thai government will cut its current account deficit to five
percent of its gross domestic product (GDP) this year from eight
percent in 1995, and to three percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The country will also try to maintain its annual economic
growth at 3-4 percent this year and next year, cap inflation at
8-9 percent this year and restore finance stability immediately
through balancing income and expenditure, reforming the finance
system, and borrowing from the IMF and other countries and
international institutions.
</P>
<P>
Under the comprehensive plan, the Thai government also
introduced some important steps to address the country's current
economic and financial problems.
</P>
<P>
The government will first of all allow the Financial
Institution Development Fund to provide guarantee for depositors
and creditors and in the future, a deposit insurance institution
will be set up for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, The Thai government will raise value added tax from
seven percent to 10 percent as from August 16 this year.
</P>
<P>
The government also will retain the managed floatation of the
baht and restrict spending to the public sector, including
education, public health, infrastructure, social welfare and
investment in state enterprise.
</P>
<P>
Thai Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya said in a statement
Tuesday that Thailand's ailing economy needs assistance from the
IMF and the painful measures will help Thailand to achieve
sustainable economic development in the long-term.
</P>
<P>
He urged people to be patient, disciplined and frugal and not
to lose heart in the struggle through economic hardship.
</P>
<P>
Thailand reportedly is seeking an initial credit line of 15 to
20 billion U.S. dollars from the IMF. The IMF has formulated an
overall rescue package, but with six conditions attached -- higher
taxes, a clean-up of the finance sector, a balanced budget,
elimination of subsidies to state agencies, tight monetary policy
and maintenance of the current foreign exchange system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
