<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Failure of Safety Device May Be Blamed for Crash: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Failure of a safety device may
be blamed for today's jumbo jet crash on Guam that killed some 200
people on board Korean Air Lines (KAL) Flight 801 bound for Agana
from Seoul, a KAL vice-president said.
</P>
<P>
Lee Tae-won said failure of a safety device used to assist
pilots during instrument landings may have caused the crash.
</P>
<P>
Guam officials have confirmed that the airport's glide slope, a
device used for instrument landings during poor visibility, had
been out of service for some time.
</P>
<P>
Lee said there were 55 survivors.
</P>
<P>
His version contradicted other accounts: U.S. navy officials
said earlier that 33 survivors had been rescued and there was
little chance of finding any others. The 747s 'black box'
recorder, however, has been found and sent to Hawaii for
examination.
</P>
<P>
A stewardess was reported to be unscathed following the crash
and was found walking about at the crash scene.
</P>
<P>
The Boeing 747, carrying 231 passengers and 23 crew members,
exploded into flaming pieces at a hilly jungle area after striking
a pipeline.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. rescue team rushed to the scene soon after the crash.
</P>
<P>
Poor visibility, shoulder-high grass and muddy conditions
hampered earlier rescue efforts. Rescue workers had to follow
screams to find those trapped in the burning wreckage and a path
had to be carved through the jungle for emergency rescue equipment.
</P>
<P>
A South Korean team of experts has also left for the crash site
to investigate the cause of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
South Korean President Kim Young-sam called an emergency
meeting of cabinet ministers and ordered all necessary support for
the rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
Relatives of those on the plane are waiting anxiously at KAL
headquarters in Seoul for news of family members and friends.
</P>
<P>
Among the 231 passengers on board the ill-fated aircraft, there
were 21 foreigners, three children and Shin Ki-ha, a four-term
lawmaker and former parliamentary leader of the main opposition
National Congress for New Politics, his wife and 20 party members.
</P>
<P>
A KAL official said Flight 801 was upgraded from an Airbus to
the larger Boeing 747-300 because of an increase in tourists to
Guam during the current summer holiday season.
</P>
<P>
Guam, the largest of the Mariana Islands, in the unincorporated
U.S. territory, is one of the most popular tourist destinations
for holidaymakers from both sides of the ocean.
</P>
<P>
Its capital Agana is dotted with five-star hotels that offer
water sports and outdoor activities. Snorkeling, scuba diving and
deep sea fishing are the most popular activities in the island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
