<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Million Nepalese Children Forced to Work: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 6 (Xinhua) -- An estimated five million child
laborers work in different sectors in Nepal and most of them are
forced to support their families, an official survey shows.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by Nepal's National Planning Commission,
said poor economic conditions are the major reason behind child
labor.
</P>
<P>
In rural areas, children work simply because of poverty, the
survey said, adding that only 10 percent of the child laborers
take up a job of their own free will.
</P>
<P>
While in urban areas, economic conditions plus parental
pressure are to be blamed. The survey found that 29 percent of the
children work for economic reasons, 20 percent due to parental
pressure and another 20 percent of their free will.
</P>
<P>
But for the bonded child laborers, poverty tells all.
</P>
<P>
The survey says almost 88 percent of them work solely for
economic reasons, eight percent due to parental pressure and a
mere one percent of their own will.
</P>
<P>
Some 54 percent of the rural child laborers and 37 percent of
the urban ones come from families heavily indebted, the survey
shows.
</P>
<P>
The survey further notes that 46 percent of the rural child
laborers and most of the urban ones come from wage earning
families.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the bonded child laborers depend on agriculture for
livelihood, the survey says.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows these child laborers are basically engaged in
five sectors: agriculture and house work (86 percent), service
sector (6 percent), business and cottage industry (three percent),
factories (2.4 percent) and construction (0.6 percent).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Country Level Consultation on Child Labor held
here Tuesday, some noted that children who go to cities become the
victims of financial, physical, mental and sexual exploitation.
</P>
<P>
Nepali newspapers quoted a senior official of the International
Labor Organization as saying that child laborers deserve to be
identified, exposed and eliminated without further delay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lima Remains One of Most Dangerous Cities in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Lima, capital of Peru, remains among
the cities with the highest crime rate in Latin America, in spite
of improvement in social security in the 1990s, a senior official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Lima is now ranked the sixth of the most dangerous city in the
region instead of the second in the late 1980s, when it was
preceded by Cali, Colombia, said Andres Bernales, chairman of
Peruvian Council of Integral Security.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Peruvian government has taken measures to
curb terrorism and other criminal acts, said Bernales. And 300
private security companies have also contributed to better social
security, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, the current situation is still very serious. So far
this year 800 abductions, four cases each day on average, have
taken place, the security official said.
</P>
<P>
Every day, five raids were committed on financial agencies and
banks, and 1,000 assaults were witnessed.
</P>
<P>
The Council has attributed the high crime rate to economic and
social unrests and a poverty-stricken population.
</P>
<P>
The five cities with the highest crime rate in Latin America
are Bogota, Rio de Janeiro, Cali, Caracas and Mexico, Bernales
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
