<HEADLINE> Australia to Give Food Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Australia would provide another
2.56 million U.S. dollars in food aid for the famine-stricken
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), Australian Minister
For Foreign Affairs Alexander Downer announced today.
</P>
<P>
Downer said the additional funding was in response to the
latest international appeal issued by the United Nations World
Food Program (WFP).
</P>
<P>
He said Australia, through the Australian Agency for
International Development or AusAID, had already provided 2.96
million U.S. dollars for food aid, including 93 tons of
Australia-made high energy biscuits, to help alleviate the food
crisis in the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
"The additional funding will contribute to the WFP's program of
increasing daily food rations for 2.6 million DPRK children aged
under six from 100 to 250 grams a day," the foreign minister said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Downer said the Australian aid would be channeled through the
WFP because it was one of the few humanitarian agencies with a
presence in the DPRK and was best able to manage and monitor food
distribution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
