<HEADLINE> Tax Collection Falls Short of Target in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's tax revenue collection
suffered a major setback in the fiscal 1996-97, forcing the
government to borrow a huge amount of money from the banks to meet
the revenue expenditure, said official sources.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, collection of tax revenue
during the last fiscal ending June this year amounted to 124.4
billion taka (about 2.86 billion U.S. dollars) as against the
target of 130.4 billion taka (about 3 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The figure, however, indicated a 9.42 percent growth compared
with the 113 billion taka (about 2.6 billion dollars) collected in
the previous fiscal.
</P>
<P>
Revenue officials attributed the shortfall mainly to frequent
congestion at Chittagong port, the largest seaport of Bangladesh,
which witnessed frequent strikes last year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that the customs duty collection during the
period came to 40.07 billion taka (about 921 million dollars),
which was 4.03 billion taka (about 92.6 million dollars) less than
the target.
</P>
<P>
To meet the revenue expenditure, the government already
borrowed 14.97 billion taka (about 344 million dollars) from the
banking sector in the last fiscal. Further increase in government
borrowing would mean higher inflation, the sources added.
</P>
</TEXT>
