<HEADLINE> Pilot Zones Tap Oceanic Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The government has selected five
pilot zones for developing the oceanic economy to pave the way for
restructuring its oceanic industrial projects and accelerating
coastal economic growth, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based newspaper quotes Zhao Jihao, vice-director of
the planning and finance department under the State Oceanographic
Administration (SOA) as saying that these zones are the Bohai Bay
Rim, the Yangtze River Estuary and the Hangzhou Bay Area, the
southeastern offshore area of Fujian province, the Pearl River
Estuary and the Beibuwan Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
The country's oceanic economy has grown rapidly over the past
two decades, as the oceanic output value reached more than 24
billion US dollars in 1995, about 30 times that of 1979.
</P>
<P>
To curb serious waste of raw materials and ease huge pressure
on environment, the national programme on oceanic resource
exploitation fixed the coastal zones as pilots for sustainable
integrated oceanic and land economic development first in the
coastal areas and later in the inland regions.
</P>
<P>
These zones have developed their oceanic economy through
constructing and expanding ports, improving techniques of aquatic
breeding and oceanic chemical industry as well as bettering the
coastal tourism service trade.
</P>
<P>
Provinces like Shandong, Liaoning, Jiangsu, Fujian and Hainan,
as well as Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, have worked out their
own plans for developing their oceanic economy under the guidance
of the national programme and have increased investment in
advancing oceanic technologies.
</P>
<P>
China claims more than 18,000 kilometers of coast line. It has
jurisdiction over three million square kilometers of sea under the
UN Convention on the Law of the Sea, the paper says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Not Interested in Slavery Apology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The White House said today
that President Bill Clinton does not consider apologizing for
slavery to be an appropriate first step for his national dialogue
on race.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said Clinton decided soon
after his June 14 speech in California on race that he was not
interested in an apology, although he said in later interviews
that he would consider the idea.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said an apology "is not the place that he chooses to
begin this dialogue.... I don't anticipate the president putting
any of the focus of his energy on that subject any time soon."
</P>
<P>
The subject did not come up Tuesday during Clinton's meeting
with the Black Leadership Forum, an umbrella group of the heads of
black organizations. The group's president said it was not
interested in talking about an apology.
</P>
<P>
However, individual members said they had made it clear to
Clinton they had not ruled out an apology, as long as it came with
something of more substance.
</P>
<P>
"An apology is in order," said Jesse Jackson, head of the
Rainbow PUSH Action Network. "But you must not only apologize with
your lips. Repent, repair and remedy go together."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said in an interview on Monday that he would leave the
matter up to his race advisory board he set up in June.
</P>
<P>
The idea of a national apology was first raised by
Representative Tony Hall, who introduced legislation calling on
Congress to apologize to black Americans whose ancestors were
slaves.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
