<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Make Artificial Rain over Dry Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government is
intensifying the production of artificial rain in drought-hit
areas in Java and South Sulawesi, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Public Works Radinal Moochtar said here Wednesday
the artificial rain-making effort would be coupled with the
building of dams to store the rain water until the rainy season.
</P>
<P>
Rainy season usually starts in September or October.
</P>
<P>
Data at the Ministry of Public Works indicate that the current
drought is having a greater impact on rice fields than previously
predicted.
</P>
<P>
Up to this week, 112,889 hectares of rice fields have been
affected by drought, of which 5,870 were totally damaged.
</P>
<P>
The situation this year, however, is not as bad as in 1994 when
544,422 hectares of rice fields were hit by drought, the minister
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
