<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwestern China Cooperating With Japan In Rice Seed Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, Aug 6 (Xinhua) -- After 15 years of joint research by
Chinese and Japanese agronomists as part of a Sino-Japanese
government agreement, the Academy of Agricultural Sciences of
China's Yunnan Province has produced 42 new varieties of high
yields, high quality, cold- and disease-resistant rice seeds.
</P>
<P>
The co-operative work has included large-scale study and
evaluation of seed heredity information, breeding, and
utilization. Chinese and Japanese agronomists provided 1,376 types
of seeds for each other to examine and studied their
cold-resistant properties and rice blast resistance, as well as
quality and yield, then chose the best for hybridizing.
</P>
<P>
The new seeds have been sown on 11.6 million mu (about 773,300
hectares) of mountainous land in Yunnan, Guizhou, Sichuan, and
western Hunan provinces in the southwestern part of China, where
freezing temperatures and rice blast caused by heavy rainfall are
common.
</P>
<P>
Per-hectare output of these new seeds was 897.3 kilograms more
than that of previously used seeds and total output increased 694
million kilograms. Half of the rice-growing areas in Yunnan have
used these new seeds this year and there has been no sign of frost
and rice-blast damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil's Diamond Production Picked Up in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's diamond
production picked up last year after a year in recession. The
output totaled 900,000 carats, mining experts said.
</P>
<P>
Diamond production in 1994 fell to 600,000 carats from the
previous year's 1,000,000 carats. But it grew by 300,000 carats
last year, said geologist Paulo Dibeiro de Santana, from the
Mining Department.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's diamond production ranks seventh in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
