<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More survivors found in S. Korean plane crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The number of persons who
survived the early morning crash of South Korean flight 801 bound
for Guam has so far reached 55, but rescue workers see little hope of
finding more, said a Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
The Boeing 747, carrying 231 passengers and 23 crew members,
crashed in a rugged jungle area at 2:35 a.m. local time Wednesday
just before landing at the Agana International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Low visibility and a driving rain have made rescue operations
difficult. So far there are no reports on the cause of the
crash.
</P>
<P>
A US rescue team rushed immediately to the crash site and began to
carve a path through the jungle for heavy rescue equipment.
</P>
<P>
The plane exploded into flaming pieces after striking an oil
pipeline, while heavy smoke shrouded the plane's wreckage.
</P>
<P>
Most of the passengers were reportedly on holiday, while some
were said to be honeymooners. No less than 13 Americans were
reported to be on board the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Guam, one of most popular destinations for South Korean tourists
and the largest of the Mariana Islands in the western Pacific, is
an unincorporated territory of the United States with a population
of about 144,000. A US military base covers one third of the
island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
