<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Specialists Leave for Guam to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 6 (Xinhua) -- An expert team formed by the Korea
Air (KAL) and South Korean government has left here 9:05 local
time on a special plane for Guam to investigate the cause of KAL
crash accident.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Construction and Transportation officially
announced on Wednesday that KAL flight KE801 crashed into a
thickly-forested mountain about 4.8 kilometers from Guam's Agana
International Airport at 01:55 a.m. local time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that around 50 people survived the accident
and the number would increase.
</P>
<P>
News from Guam said that 55 out of the 254 passengers and crew
members were hospitalized in Guam as of 8:00 local time (0:00 GMT
Wednesday). It was soon confirmed by KAL.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Koh Kun held an emergency meeting with ministers
for foreign affairs, construction and transportation and
government administration at 5:00 a.m. and set up a headquarters
to control the situation.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters has sent a seven-member team of specialists
along with KAL experts to the accident scene in Guam, who will
investigate the cause of the crash and help the rescue work.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Guam said the black box has been found near the
crash scene and the cause of the crash is to be cleared later.
</P>
</TEXT>
