<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT: South Korean Air Jet Crashes in Guam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A South Korean air plane with 254
passengers and crew members on board crashed in a forest near Guam
at around 01:55 Wednesday Korean Standard Time (04:55 GMT
Tuesday), (South) Korea Air (KAL) said.
</P>
<P>
The plane crashed shortly before it arrived at the Guam
International Airport, said Kal.
</P>
<P>
Of the passengers, about 50 people were rescued as of 5 a.m.,
it was learned.
</P>
<P>
The KAL flight KE801 took off Kimpo International Airport at
8:20 p.m. Tuesday for Guam.
</P>
<P>
KAL officials said the passengers, most of whom were Koreans,
included about 13 Americans and 2 Japanese.
</P>
<P>
The 385-seat Boeing 747-300B was imported in December 1984, KAL
said.
</P>
<P>
Lee Tae-won, vice president of KAL, said that Typhoon Tina was
approaching Guam when the accident happened. "There was a report
that an automatic landing equipment on the airport was out of
order."
</P>
<P>
Forty-nine survivors were sent to the Memorial Hospital in
Guam, he said.
</P>
<P>
The last message from the plane was "something wrong," Lee
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
