<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Air Crash at Guam Kills More Than 200 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A South Korean Air jumbo jet
with 254 people aboard crashed off Guam early Wednesday (local
time) when it was trying to land at Guam's A.B. Won Pat
International Airport, killing more than 200 people.
</P>
<P>
Guam police said that about 30 people survived the crash that
happened five kilometers from the airport at about 1:50 a.m. local
time (11:50 p.m. EDT Tuesday).
</P>
<P>
The airline said the plane was carrying 254 people -- 231
passengers and 23 crewmen. Most of the passengers were Korean
tourists and honeymooners.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports from different sources had put the number on
board the Boeing 747 at between 231 and 331.
</P>
<P>
Flight 801 from Seoul, South Korea, to Guam was cleared to land
when contact was lost at the distance, the U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration's Pacific officials in Honolulu said.
</P>
<P>
Some witnesses said that they saw flames or heard an explosion
before the plane went down in a rain storm in the hills.
</P>
<P>
An Associated Press report quoted a White House official as
saying that the pilot radioed the tower, declared an in-flight
emergency and said "there was a fire on board."
</P>
<P>
A landing system known as the glide slope, which leads planes
to the runway, had not been in service at the airport since last
month, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The National Transportation Safety Board was sending a team of
12 officials from Washington to investigate. U.S. military forces
at Guam took part in the rescue work, hoping to find more
survivors.
</P>
<P>
The plane ordinarily lands at Guam and then returns to Seoul as
Flight 802, according to the current International Passenger
Timetable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House to Study Recommendations on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The White House said today it
will "seriously" consider a federal advisory panel's
recommendations abolishing the Immigration and Naturalization
Service (INS) and reassigning its duties.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Commission on Immigration Reform, in its fourth and
final report since its creation by Congress in 1990, was expected
to recommend the INS's duties be divided among the departments of
state, justice and labor.
</P>
<P>
The INS has been criticized for failing to cope with rapidly
growing requests for citizenship, and failing to crack down on
criminal aliens and illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
White House press secretary Mike McCurry said the commission's
report identified "not shortcomings in the personnel and people,
but structural impediments to them efficiently doing their job
because of overlapping jurisdictions of other departments."
</P>
<P>
McCurry said the White House has not yet taken a position on
the report, saying, "It is clearly an agency that deals with some
of the most complex problems we face in our society, and at times
its performance falls short."
</P>
<P>
The commission planned to recommend that the Justice Department
take responsibility for border control and removal of illegal
immigrants, the State Department handle immigration services and
benefits, and the Labor Department enforce rules covering the
hiring of foreign workers, according to The New York Times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
