<DOCNO> XIE19970806.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US: Israel's Economic Weapon "Counterproductive" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States today called
Israel's suspension of its reimbursement of taxes owed to the
Palestinian Authority "counterproductive" to the peace process in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley called on Israel to
resume the reimbursement in accordance with its agreements with
the Palestinians to transfer to the Palestinian Authority of
nearly 500 million dollars that it collects each year from
Palestinians who work or buy goods in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Foley said Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat "referred to the
hardships the Palestinians are undergoing under these
circumstances," when he conversed through telephone with Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright today.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government unleashed the economic weapon by
suspending the reimbursement as part of its campaign to impose
pressure on the Palestinian Authority in the wake of last week's
bombings at a Jerusalem produce market, which killed 15 people
and injured more than 100.
</P>
<P>
Foley said Albright will speak to Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu later today, but he did not said what they will
discuss.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Arafat offered his assurances in his
telephone conversations with Albright about his commitment to
security for the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
"He's been saying the right things," Foley said. And he said
the United States "wants to see sustained efforts" by the
Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
Foley also said U.S. mediator Dennis Ross will travel to the
Middle East this weekend, where he will meet Arafat, Netanyahu
and possibly other Middle East leaders.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who has shunned the shuttle diplomacy strategy used
by her predecessors to push Middle East peaceful settlements,
will also go to the region soon after Ross's mission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
